 Astafyev]] (9 / 3), [[Yevgeni Tarasov (footballer, born 1979)|Yevgeni Tarasov]] {{flagicon|KAZ}} (9 / 3), [[Dmitri Akimov]] (2), [[Dzmitry Aharodnik]] {{flagicon|BLR}} (2), [[Aleksandr Petukhov (Russian footballer, born 1980)|Aleksandr Petukhov]] (1).\n\nOne own goal scored by [[Otar Khizaneishvili]] {{flagicon|GEO}} ([[FC Rostselmash Rostov-on-Don]]).\n\n'''Manager:''' [[Yury Morozov (footballer, born 1934)|Yury Morozov]].\n\n'''Transferred out during the season:''' none.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2001 in Russian football]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesr/rus01.html RSSSF]\n\n{{Russian Premier League seasons}}\n{{2000\u201301 in European football (UEFA)}}\n{{2001\u201302 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n[[Category:Russian Premier League seasons|2001]]\n[[Category:2001 in Russian football leagues|1]]\n[[Category:2001\u201302 in European association football leagues|Russia]]\n[[Category:2000\u201301 in European association football leagues|Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStandings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2001_Russian_Top_Division"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Coutts (colonist)", "text_new": "'''Thomas Coutts''' (11 December 1797 \u2013 14 January 1868) was a Scottish colonist who moved to Australia during the 19th century establishing various enterprises including [[whaling in Australia|whaling]] and [[pastoral farming]] businesses. He is best known for perpetrating a [[mass poisonings of Aboriginal Australians|mass poisoning]] of [[Aboriginal Australians]] on a property near the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] in the [[Northern Rivers]] area of [[New South Wales]], which killed at least 23 people. Although Coutts was arrested for this crime, the judicial authorities never put the case to trial and he was released after the payment of bail. Coutts afterwards became a prosperous and respected colonial figure. The town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] is named after him.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Coutts was born in [[Glenmuick]], [[Aberdeenshire]] in [[Scotland]] on 11 December 1797. His parents were James and Elizabeth Coutts.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gordon Family Tree |url=https://sites.rootsweb.com/~gordon/gordonfam/pafg43.htm#1345 |website=Rootsweb |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He emigrated with two of his brothers to the British colony of New South Wales around 1817. He settled in Sydney and it appears that Coutts chose to follow a seafaring vocation. By the 1830s he became a [[master mariner]], taking the title of Captain Thomas Coutts.<ref name=\"couttsclan\">{{cite web |last1=Coutts |first1=Malcolm |title=Capt Thomas & Rev James |url=https://clancoutts.ning.com/page/capt-thomas-rev-james |website=Clan Coutts Society |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Whaling==\nIn 1832, Coutts and his brothers built a 90 tonne [[brig]] on the banks of the [[Georges River]]. They named the vessel the ''Lady Leith'' and Thomas Coutts was registered as both the owner and master of the brig. Initially the ''Lady Leith'' was utilised to transport cargo from Sydney to [[Hobart]] but soon was trading in sugar between [[Mauritius]] and Australia. It seems this wasn't a profitable trade as Coutts quickly switched to using his vessel as a whaler.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> From the mid 1830s until 1840, Coutts captained the ''Lady Leith'' in regular voyages to the whaling grounds off New Zealand, returning with cargoes of [[sperm whale]] oil for sale in Sydney.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31722620 |title=Projected Departures|newspaper=[[The Colonist]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 February 1839 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> During this period, Coutts married Maria Bloodworth in 1834 and bought a house in O'Connell Street in Sydney.<ref name=\"couttsfam\">{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=http://www.whosyerdad-e.com/families-w/individual.php?pid=I2292&ged=white.ged |website=whosyerdad-e |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pastoral farming==\nIn early 1840, Coutts placed the ''Lady Leith'' up for sale and started to invest in [[pastoral farming]]. He and several other [[Squatting (Australian history)|squatters]] took the opportunity of purchasing and droving herds of livestock to the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] region where they could occupy supposedly vacant crown land. They were guided by an ex-convict in [[Richard Craig (adventurer)|Richard Craig]] who had previously lived with the [[Gumbaynggirr]] and [[Bundjalung people]] in this area after he escaped from the [[Moreton Bay penal settlement]]. Initially Coutts set up a [[sheep station]] called Bald Hills in the [[New England (New South Wales)|New England]] region which was at the start of the track down to the Clarence River valley. Coutts Water which was part of his Bald Hills property, is a waterway that still bears his name and is now a popular trout fishing site.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coutts Water |url=https://mapio.net/pic/p-37539788/ |website=mapio |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1840, Coutts, led by Richard Craig, brought around two thousand head of sheep and cattle down the track from Bald Hills to the Clarence River valley.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476493 |title=Thomas Courts|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> He laid claim to a region of open and lightly wooded country south of the river and named this leasehold Kangaroo Creek. The region was of course already occupied by [[Aboriginal Australians]] and Coutts proceeded to take ownership of the land forcibly from the original inhabitants. In response, the local Gumbaynggirr people killed Coutts' cattle and sheep and also killed several of Coutts' stockmen.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article193844192 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 July 1937 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> Detachments of [[Border Police of New South Wales|Border Police]] occassionally massacred local Aboriginal people in punitive expeditions in order to protect the local British squatters, but small scale Aboriginal resistance around Kangaroo Creek continued throughout the 1840s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28651627 |title=Domestic Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=9 July 1841 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\n==Mass poisoning at Kangaroo Creek==\nIn late November 1847, Coutts invited the Aboriginal people living around Kangaroo Creek to come to his homestead for the possibility of obtaining work. Coutts had previously not allowed any groups of Aboriginal people near his homestead and was widely known to have expressed the opinion that native people \"deserved shooting\".{{cite quote|date=April 2020}} Around 23 people accepted the offer and Coutts put them to work weeding areas close to the homestead. After the work was completed, Coutts gave them a 10 pound bag of flour. Coutts was observed to have put the powdery contents of a paper sachet, believed to have been [[arsenic]], into the bag of flour before giving it to the group of Gumbaynggirr. The unsuspecting people took the bag of poisoned flour from Coutts and proceeded to a communal area in the hills between Kangaroo and Towallum Creeks. Here, they made damper from the flour and ate it.<ref name=\"lydon\" >{{Citation | author1=Lydon, Jane | title='no moral doubt...' : Aboriginal evidence and the Kangaroo Creek poisoning, 1847\u20131849 | publication-date=1996 | url=https://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/p72561/pdf/article0714.pdf | accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476489 |title=Poisoned Blacks|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nA couple of days later, several reports emerged of a large number of Aboriginal people becoming violently ill and dying in the hills behind Kangaroo Creek. The local Commissioner for Crown Lands, Oliver Fry, heard these reports from both white and black sources, and came to investigate. In January 1848, Fry visited the site and found the decomposing bodies of at least 23 people. He collected evidence including remnants of the damper that remained, and immediately arrested and charged Coutts for the crime. Local magistrates concluded Coutts should stand trial for wilful murder and he was transported to Sydney to be tried at the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\nOn 23 February, Coutts appeared before judge [[Alfred Stephen]] and was given bail on \u00a31,000 worth of sureties. The case was delayed and on 10 May 1848, the Attorney General, [[John Plunkett]], decided not to proceed with the case. Plunkett did this even though he had a very strong suspicion of Coutts' guilt and was aware that justice was being \"entirely evaded\" by this decision. Coutts was subsequently discharged and returned to Kangaroo Creek.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\n==Moving northwards==\nDuring his time at Sydney, one of Coutts' hutkeepers at Kangaroo Creek was killed by local Gumbaynggirr in an apparent revenge attack. Coutts quickly sold out of his Kangaroo Creek holdings and in 1850 he took up the [[Tooloom Creek|Tooloom]] property in the ranges about 100km to the north of [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]]. He also invested in a steamer named the ''Raven'' which provided a river transport service between [[Brisbane]] and [[Ipswich, Queensland|Ipswich]]. In 1851, Coutts looked to gain further property by taking a large flock of sheep further north to squat on land near to [[Camboon, Queensland|Camboon]] on the [[Dawson River (Queensland)|Dawson River]]. This region was being strongly defended from British colonisation by the resident [[Yiman people]] who killed several of Coutts' shepherds and speared to death Alexander \"Sandy\" Ross, who was a squatter accompanying Coutts in his attempt to set up a property. Due to the resistance of the Yiman, Coutts was forced to abandon the Dawson River and returned to Tooloom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article677024 |title=Central Criminal Court|newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 December 1851 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> A few years later, he bought the [[Ellangowan, Queensland|Ellangowan]] property near [[Toowoomba]]. His wife died at this property in 1856 and the following year Coutts sold the ''Raven''.\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1859, Coutts decided to retire from the violent yet profitable frontier pastoralist lifestyle and bought a mansion in the waterside Sydney suburb of [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] where he stayed until 1866.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> The residence he purchased, known as \"Balmoral House\", still exists today under that name at 46 Waterview Street in Balmain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Balmoral House |url=https://balmainwalks.org.au/tb_walk_stop/balmoral-house/ |website=Balmain Walks |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1866, Coutts decided to return to the land and purchased the [[Toolburra, Queensland|North Toolburra]] property near [[Warwick, Queensland|Warwick]] in the recently created British colony of [[Queensland]]. By this stage, this area was hundreds of kilometres within the brutal frontier of British invasion but Coutts still managed to meet his death at Toolburra soon after moving there. In January 1868, Coutts walked under a tree that was being felled on this property and was hit on the head by a large branch which killed him instantly. A large funeral was organised at Warwick and he is buried in the Coutts family plot at [[Warwick General Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article82096059 |title=The Accidental Death of Thomas Coutts, Esq. |newspaper=[[Warwick Examiner and Times]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=18 January 1868 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/181981281/thomas-coutts |website=Find a Grave |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family and legacy==\nThomas Coutts had two notable brothers, one of which was Donald Coutts who accompanied Thomas throughout most of his pastoral pursuits. Donald took over the running of Tooloom from Thomas and also took up the Rosewood leasehold near Ipswich. Donald, like Thomas, was involved in a number of major incidents of frontier violence with Aboriginal people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3716180 |title=Local Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Moreton Bay Courier]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=5 September 1846 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> Thomas' other brother was Reverend James Coutts who was a minister at [[Parramatta]] and then [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] and is known for the establishment of the [[Coutt's Sailors Home]] in the latter city.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" />\n\nThomas Coutts had nine children with Maria Bloodworth with many marrying into well respected colonial families.<ref name=\"couttsfam\" />\n\nSeveral landmarks are named after Thomas Coutts. This includes town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] near [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]], the distinctive mountain outside the town of [[Urbenville, New South Wales|Urbenville]] known as Coutts Crown, and the Coutts Water stream near [[Ebor, New South Wales|Ebor]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article191783247 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[The Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 October 1938 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref> In 2018, a vote was taken by the residents of Coutts Crossing to rename their town to avoid being associated with Thomas Coutts. The residents overwhelmingly decided to retain Coutts Crossing as the town's title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harper |first1=Donna |title=Coutts Crossing villagers vote against name change despite links to brutal past |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-06-29/coutts-crossing-residents-keep-town-name-despite-a-murky-past/9921206 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=ABC News |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coutts, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1797 deaths]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeenshire]]\n[[Category:Australian pastoralists]]\n[[Category:Poisoners]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Coutts''' (11 December 1797 \u2013 14 January 1868) was a Scottish colonist who moved to Australia during the 19th century establishing various enterprises including [[whaling in Australia|whaling]] and [[pastoral farming]] businesses. He is best known for perpetrating a [[mass poisonings of Aboriginal Australians|mass poisoning]] of [[Aboriginal Australians]] on a property near the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] in the [[Northern Rivers]] area of [[New South Wales]], which killed at least 23 people. Although Coutts was arrested for this crime, the judicial authorities never put the case to trial and he was released after the payment of bail. Coutts afterwards became a prosperous and respected colonial figure. The town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] is named after him.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Coutts was born in [[Glenmuick]], [[Aberdeenshire]] in [[Scotland]] on 11 December 1797. His parents were James and Elizabeth Coutts.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gordon Family Tree |url=https://sites.rootsweb.com/~gordon/gordonfam/pafg43.htm#1345 |website=Rootsweb |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He emigrated with two of his brothers to the British colony of New South Wales around 1817. He settled in Sydney and it appears that Coutts chose to follow a seafaring vocation. By the 1830s he became a [[master mariner]], taking the title of Captain Thomas Coutts.<ref name=\"couttsclan\">{{cite web |last1=Coutts |first1=Malcolm |title=Capt Thomas & Rev James |url=https://clancoutts.ning.com/page/capt-thomas-rev-james |website=Clan Coutts Society |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Whaling==\nIn 1832, Coutts and his brothers built a 90 tonne [[brig]] on the banks of the [[Georges River]]. They named the vessel the ''Lady Leith'' and Thomas Coutts was registered as both the owner and master of the brig. Initially the ''Lady Leith'' was utilised to transport cargo from Sydney to [[Hobart]] but soon was trading in sugar between [[Mauritius]] and Australia. It seems this wasn't a profitable trade as Coutts quickly switched to using his vessel as a whaler.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> From the mid 1830s until 1840, Coutts captained the ''Lady Leith'' in regular voyages to the whaling grounds off New Zealand, returning with cargoes of [[sperm whale]] oil for sale in Sydney.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31722620 |title=Projected Departures|newspaper=[[The Colonist]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=23 February 1839 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> During this period, Coutts married Maria Bloodworth in 1834 and bought a house in O'Connell Street in Sydney.<ref name=\"couttsfam\">{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=http://www.whosyerdad-e.com/families-w/individual.php?pid=I2292&ged=white.ged |website=whosyerdad-e |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pastoral farming==\nIn early 1840, Coutts placed the ''Lady Leith'' up for sale and started to invest in [[pastoral farming]]. He and several other [[Squatting (Australian history)|squatters]] took the opportunity of purchasing and droving herds of livestock to the [[Clarence River (New South Wales)|Clarence River]] region where they could occupy supposedly vacant crown land. They were guided by an ex-convict in [[Richard Craig (adventurer)|Richard Craig]] who had previously lived with the [[Gumbaynggirr]] and [[Bundjalung people]] in this area after he escaped from the [[Moreton Bay penal settlement]]. Initially Coutts set up a [[sheep station]] called Bald Hills in the [[New England (New South Wales)|New England]] region which was at the start of the track down to the Clarence River valley. Coutts Water which was part of his Bald Hills property, is a waterway that still bears his name and is now a popular trout fishing site.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coutts Water |url=https://mapio.net/pic/p-37539788/ |website=mapio |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1840, Coutts, led by Richard Craig, brought around two thousand head of sheep and cattle down the track from Bald Hills to the Clarence River valley.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476493 |title=Thomas Courts|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> He laid claim to a region of open and lightly wooded country south of the river and named this leasehold Kangaroo Creek. The region was of course already occupied by [[Aboriginal Australians]] and Coutts proceeded to take ownership of the land forcibly from the original inhabitants. In response, the local Gumbaynggirr people killed Coutts' cattle and sheep and also killed several of Coutts' stockmen.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article193844192 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 July 1937 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref> Detachments of [[Border Police of New South Wales|Border Police]] occassionally massacred local Aboriginal people in punitive expeditions in order to protect the local British squatters, but small scale Aboriginal resistance around Kangaroo Creek continued throughout the 1840s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28651627 |title=Domestic Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=9 July 1841 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\n==Mass poisoning at Kangaroo Creek==\nIn late November 1847, Coutts invited the Aboriginal people living around Kangaroo Creek to come to his homestead for the possibility of obtaining work. Coutts had previously not allowed any groups of Aboriginal people near his homestead and was widely known to have expressed the opinion that native people \"deserved shooting\".{{cite quote|date=April 2020}} Around 23 people accepted the offer and Coutts put them to work weeding areas close to the homestead. After the work was completed, Coutts gave them a 10 pound bag of flour. Coutts was observed to have put the powdery contents of a paper sachet, believed to have been [[arsenic]], into the bag of flour before giving it to the group of Gumbaynggirr. The unsuspecting people took the bag of poisoned flour from Coutts and proceeded to a communal area in the hills between Kangaroo and Towallum Creeks. Here, they made damper from the flour and ate it.<ref name=\"lydon\" >{{Citation | author1=Lydon, Jane | title='no moral doubt...' : Aboriginal evidence and the Kangaroo Creek poisoning, 1847\u20131849 | publication-date=1996 | url=https://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/p72561/pdf/article0714.pdf | accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141476489 |title=Poisoned Blacks|newspaper=[[Dungog Chronicle : Durham and Gloucester Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=27 April 1934 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nA couple of days later, several reports emerged of a large number of Aboriginal people becoming violently ill and dying in the hills behind Kangaroo Creek. The local Commissioner for Crown Lands, Oliver Fry, heard these reports from both white and black sources, and came to investigate. In January 1848, Fry visited the site and found the decomposing bodies of at least 23 people. He collected evidence including remnants of the damper that remained, and immediately arrested and charged Coutts for the crime. Local magistrates concluded Coutts should stand trial for wilful murder and he was transported to Sydney to be tried at the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\nOn 23 February, Coutts appeared before judge [[Alfred Stephen]] and was given bail on \u00a31,000 worth of sureties. The case was delayed and on 10 May 1848, the Attorney General, [[John Plunkett]], decided not to proceed with the case. Plunkett did this even though he had a very strong suspicion of Coutts' guilt and was aware that justice was being \"entirely evaded\" by this decision. Coutts was subsequently discharged and returned to Kangaroo Creek.<ref name=\"lydon\" />\n\n==Moving northwards==\nDuring his time at Sydney, one of Coutts' hutkeepers at Kangaroo Creek was killed by local Gumbaynggirr in an apparent revenge attack. Coutts quickly sold out of his Kangaroo Creek holdings and in 1850 he took up the [[Tooloom Creek|Tooloom]] property in the ranges about 100km to the north of [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]]. He also invested in a steamer named the ''Raven'' which provided a river transport service between [[Brisbane]] and [[Ipswich, Queensland|Ipswich]]. In 1851, Coutts looked to gain further property by taking a large flock of sheep further north to squat on land near to [[Camboon, Queensland|Camboon]] on the [[Dawson River (Queensland)|Dawson River]]. This region was being strongly defended from British colonisation by the resident [[Yiman people]] who killed several of Coutts' shepherds and speared to death Alexander \"Sandy\" Ross, who was a squatter accompanying Coutts in his attempt to set up a property. Due to the resistance of the Yiman, Coutts was forced to abandon the Dawson River and returned to Tooloom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article677024 |title=Central Criminal Court|newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=6 December 1851 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> A few years later, he bought the [[Ellangowan, Queensland|Ellangowan]] property near [[Toowoomba]]. His wife died at this property in 1856 and the following year Coutts sold the ''Raven''.\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1859, Coutts decided to retire from the violent yet profitable frontier pastoralist lifestyle and bought a mansion in the waterside Sydney suburb of [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] where he stayed until 1866.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" /> The residence he purchased, known as \"Balmoral House\", still exists today under that name at 46 Waterview Street in Balmain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Balmoral House |url=https://balmainwalks.org.au/tb_walk_stop/balmoral-house/ |website=Balmain Walks |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In 1866, Coutts decided to return to the land and purchased the [[Toolburra, Queensland|North Toolburra]] property near [[Warwick, Queensland|Warwick]] in the recently created British colony of [[Queensland]]. By this stage, this area was hundreds of kilometres within the brutal frontier of British invasion but Coutts still managed to meet his death at Toolburra soon after moving there. In January 1868, Coutts walked under a tree that was being felled on this property and was hit on the head by a large branch which killed him instantly. A large funeral was organised at Warwick and he is buried in the Coutts family plot at [[Warwick General Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article82096059 |title=The Accidental Death of Thomas Coutts, Esq. |newspaper=[[Warwick Examiner And Times]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=18 January 1868 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thomas Coutts |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/181981281/thomas-coutts |website=Find a Grave |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Family and legacy==\nThomas Coutts had two notable brothers, one of which was Donald Coutts who accompanied Thomas throughout most of his pastoral pursuits. Donald took over the running of Tooloom from Thomas and also took up the Rosewood leasehold near Ipswich. Donald, like Thomas, was involved in a number of major incidents of frontier violence with Aboriginal people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3716180 |title=Local Intelligence|newspaper=[[The Moreton Bay Courier]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=5 September 1846 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> Thomas' other brother was Reverend James Coutts who was a minister at [[Parramatta]] and then [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] and is known for the establishment of the [[Coutt's Sailors Home]] in the latter city.<ref name=\"couttsclan\" />\n\nThomas Coutts had nine children with Maria Bloodworth with many marrying into well respected colonial families.<ref name=\"couttsfam\" />\n\nSeveral landmarks are named after Thomas Coutts. This includes town of [[Coutts Crossing, New South Wales|Coutts Crossing]] near [[Grafton, New South Wales|Grafton]], the distinctive mountain outside the town of [[Urbenville, New South Wales|Urbenville]] known as Coutts Crown, and the Coutts Water stream near [[Ebor, New South Wales|Ebor]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article191783247 |title=Clarence River Historical Society |newspaper=[[The Daily Examiner]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=15 October 1938 |access-date=5 April 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref> In 2018, a vote was taken by the residents of Coutts Crossing to rename their town to avoid being associated with Thomas Coutts. The residents overwhelmingly decided to retain Coutts Crossing as the town's title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harper |first1=Donna |title=Coutts Crossing villagers vote against name change despite links to brutal past |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-06-29/coutts-crossing-residents-keep-town-name-despite-a-murky-past/9921206 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |agency=ABC News |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coutts, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1797 deaths]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeenshire]]\n[[Category:Australian pastoralists]]\n[[Category:Poisoners]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Coutts_(colonist)"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Marcia King", "text_new": "{{short description|Formerly unidentified murder victim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marcia King\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = File:Marcia King.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| alt                = \n| birth_name         = Marcia Lenore King\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1959|6|9}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Body of 'Buckskin Girl' Found in Ohio in 1981 Identified as Arkansas Woman|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/body-buckskin-girl-found-ohio-1981-identified-arkansas/story?id=54417156|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=[[American Broadcasting Company]]|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| disappeared_date   = Circa 1980<!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]], [[Arkansas]], U.S.<ref name=\"tdn\"/>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1981|04|22|1959|06|09}} <ref name=namus/> <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Homicide]] by [[strangulation]]\n| body_discovered    = April 24, 1981\n| resting_place      = Riverside Cemetery, Troy, Miami County, Ohio\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|39.9660|N|84.3256|W|region:US-OH_type:landmark|display=inline}} (approximate) <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| parents            = Jonathan W. Sossoman\u2020 <br />Bonnie Bryant-King<ref name=\"penwell\">{{cite web |title=Jack W. Sossoman |url=https://www.penwellgabeltopeka.com/Obituary/152633/Jack-Sossoman/Topeka-Kansas |publisher=Penwell-Gabel Home Send Flowers |accessdate=30 August 2018 |date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Formerly unidentified victim of homicide\n| height             = {{height|ft=5|in=5|abbr=mos}} (approximate)\n| weight             = \n}}\n\n'''Marcia Lenore Sossoman (King)'''<!-- Use name that the family had inscribed on her gravestone --><ref name=\"sossoman\" /> ({{Birth date|1959|6|9}} \u2013 {{Death date|1981|04|22}}) was a 21-year-old [[Arkansas]] woman who was murdered in April 1981 and whose body was discovered in [[Troy, Ohio]] approximately forty-eight hours after her murder. Her body remained unidentified for 36 years before being identified via [[DNA analysis]] and [[genetic genealogy]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> King was the first [[unidentified decedent]] to be identified via this method of [[Forensic science|forensic investigation]].<ref name=\"timeline\" /><ref name=\"miamiID\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Sheriff's Office Identifies 1981 Cold Case Victim|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 11, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her 2018 identification, King was informally known as \"'''Buckskin Girl'''\" and \"'''Miami County [[Jane Doe]]'''\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spain|first1=Jamie|title=37 Years After Young Woman's Mysterious Slaying, She is Finally Identified|url=https://people.com/crime/buckskin-girl-found-dead-ohio-identified-37-year-later/|accessdate=March 22, 2020|work=People|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> The first of these two names is in reference to the distinctive tasseled [[buckskin (leather)|buckskin]] poncho<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> she was wearing at the time of her discovery.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help />\n\nFollowing the identification of her body, Marcia King's family erected a new headstone at her grave in Riverside Cemetery, inscribed with her actual name. The investigation into her murder is ongoing.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\n==Discovery==\nOn April 24, 1981, three young men discovered the body of a young [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] woman in a ditch alongside Greenlee Road in [[Newton Township, Miami County, Ohio|Newton Township]], [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], Ohio.<ref name=still>{{cite news|title=Victim Still Unidentified|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1904&stc=1&d=1332268098|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 30, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Helen|title=Amateur Sleuths Restore Identity to the Dead|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Amateur-sleuths-restore-identity-to-the-dead-3219899.php|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=Seattle Post Intelligencer|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref> One of the three men, Greg Bridenbaugh, initially noticed the decedent's distinctive buckskin poncho. Informing one of his companions, Neal Hoffman, to take a look at the coat, Hoffman walked closer to the article of clothing before turning toward Bridenbaugh, stating: \"Oh my God, there's a woman in that coat!\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Buckskin Gril' Identified|url=https://www.tdn-net.com/top-stories/39213/buckskin-girl-identified|accessdate=April 4, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|These members of the public had first noticed the decedent's deerskin poncho lying alongside Greenlee Road before discovering her body.<ref name=\"whio\" />}} The young woman was lying in a [[fetal position]], on her right side, and without shoes or socks.<ref name=\"tdn\" /><ref name=namus>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4790|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/4790|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=7 November 2014|date=10 December 2008}}</ref> These members of the public called police to report their discovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Autopsy===\nThe decedent's body was autopsied on the afternoon of her discovery. The medical examination revealed she had suffered extensive [[Blunt trauma|blunt force trauma]] to the head and neck,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullen|first1=Shannon|title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey?|url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116/|accessdate=March 31, 2020|date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> before she had been strangled to death<ref name=still/> approximately forty-eight hours before her body was discovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buckskin Girl|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/|website=dnadoeproject.org|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In addition, her liver had also been lacerated.<ref name=ramsey>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=Rachelle|title=Jane Doe Doesn't Have a Name or Suspect|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1999&stc=1&d=1348637351|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=August 29, 1994}}</ref> She had not been subjected to any form of [[sexual assault]].<ref name=jim>{{cite news|last1=DeBrosse|first1=Jim|title='Somebody Cares About Them. We Do': Jane Doe Cases Could be Solved 'Overnight' if Database Utilized, Police Say|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/media/news155.html|accessdate=June 1, 2014|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|date=August 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe woman had been between {{cvt|5|ft|4|in|cm}} and {{cvt|5|ft|6|in|cm}} in height, aged between eighteen and twenty-six, and weighed {{convert|125|-|130|lb}}.<ref name=cause/><ref name=id/> She had naturally reddish-brown hair, which was braided into pigtails on both sides of her head.<ref name=doe/><ref name=help/><ref name=id/><ref name=cause>{{cite news|title=Strangulation Cause of Death|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1897&stc=1&d=1332267864|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 27, 1981}}</ref> Her eyes were light brown in color, and she had freckles across her face.<ref name=doe/> In addition, her nose was described as being \"very pointed\".<ref name=watch/> The victim also had a ruddy complexion, indicating she had spent a lot of time outdoors in the final weeks or months of her life.<ref name=doe /><ref name=tri/>\n\nThe young woman had maintained a high level of personal hygiene. All her teeth, including her [[Wisdom tooth|wisdom teeth]], were in good condition and had no evidence of [[Dental restoration|fillings]] or other dental work, except for one porcelain [[Crown (dentistry)|crown]] upon her upper-right [[incisor]].<ref name=namus/><ref name=BGNCMEC/> The coroner also noted several scars upon her body, including a vertical scar beneath her chin, with other scars also visible upon one wrist, both arms, and one ankle.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami>{{cite web |title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981 |url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210190938/http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |year=2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Clothing===\nThe young woman was dressed in blue bell-bottom [[Wrangler (jeans)|Wrangler]] jeans, a brown turtleneck pullover sweater with an orange crisscross design on the front, a white size 32D bra,<ref name=doe/> and a hoodless deerskin poncho with purple lining, which appeared to be handmade.<ref name=tri>{{cite web|title=Miami County Jane Doe, OH |url=http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414175922/http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |archivedate=April 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=help>{{cite web|last=Besso |first=Donna |title=Need Help Identifying \"The Buckskin Girl\" |url=http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414195811/http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |date=July 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=oh>{{cite web|title=Ohio Unsolved Homicides|url=http://www.ohioattorneygeneral.gov/Files/Law-Enforcement/Investigator/Unidentified-Remains|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> She wore no shoes or socks.<ref name=id>{{cite web|title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiOhioJaneDoeApril1981|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> No form of identification was located upon her body or at the crime scene.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami/>\n\n==Initial investigation==\nBecause the decedent's body was found approximately forty-eight hours after her death,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> police were able to obtain her [[fingerprints]] and dental information. The [[Dental notation|dental charts]] and fingerprints of this decedent yielded no results matching her to any known missing person, and her fingerprints matched no police records, indicating she had no criminal record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> Early police efforts to identify this decedent also involved the creation of a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of her face which was published in local newspapers and broadcast on television networks on April 28, 1981.<ref name=no>{{cite news|title=No identification Yet|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1898&stc=1&d=1332267912|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 28, 1981}}</ref> This initial media publicity surrounding the murder generated approximately two hundred leads. Although all were investigated, all failed to bear fruition.<ref name=still/>\n\nThe victim gradually became known as \"Buckskin Girl\" in reference to the distinctive tasseled buckskin jacket she was wearing when found.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help /><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neill|first1=Helen|title=Volunteers Use Computers to Name the Dead|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/news/2008-03-29-naming-dead_N.htm|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=Associated Press|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref> The failure to establish her identity hindered investigators' efforts to solve her murder. As her identity remained undiscovered, investigating authorities came to increasingly believe the reason Buckskin Girl remained unidentified had been due to the fact that she had been murdered far from her hometown.<ref name=\"perspectives\" /> A retired investigator is also known to have opined his belief the decedent was highly unlikely to have originated from the area where she was discovered.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nAuthorities strongly believed Buckskin Girl had been murdered elsewhere and her body discarded beside the road shortly after her death.<ref name=no/><ref name=cause/> This conclusion was supported by the fact her bare feet were clean, showing no indication of her having walked upon a dirty surface, and because [[Interstate 75]] is just {{convert|5|mi|0|spell=in}} from where her body was recovered, making the site a convenient and discreet location to discard a body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/news/projects/ourstories/10570633-74/doe-jane-hickey|title=Slain Jane Doe's Curious Case in Ohio Still Puzzles After 35 Years|first=Chris|last=Togneri|date=June 4, 2016|website=TribLIVE.com}}</ref> Police and the media later speculated that she may have been a teenage runaway or a possible victim of a serial killer known to have murdered several sex workers in the region during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=jim/><ref name=doe/><ref name=tri/> However, her body had not been subjected to any form of sexual assault, indicating she was unlikely to have been a sex worker.<ref name=doe/>\n\nThe investigation into Buckskin Girl's murder gradually became a [[cold case]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Jane Doe No More: Miami County Sheriff IDs Cold Case Victim 37 Years Later|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=[[WHIO-TV]]|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> although police and other officials continued to investigate her murder. Her clothing and other [[physical evidence]] recovered at the crime scene was retained, and a sample of her blood preserved.<ref name=\"whio\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Authorities Still Working on Jane Doe Case|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425044702/http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|archive-date=April 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Theories==\n===Lifestyle===\nInvestigators theorized that Buckskin Girl had been a runaway teenager, a foster child, or a transient wanderer unlikely to have spent a significant period of time in Ohio prior to her death, although her high quality of personal hygiene strongly indicated that she had not lived as a vagrant.<ref name=doe/> As her body was located close to a town road instead of a highway, the probability of her being a wanderer for a significant amount of time was considered to be negligible.<ref name=watch/> The absence of her footwear at the crime scene led some investigators to believe she may have been murdered by an abusive partner.<ref name=watch>{{cite web | url=http://crimewatchdaily.com/2015/10/19/help-crime-watch-daily-and-carl-koppelman-give-names-to-these-5-murder-victims/ | title=Help Crime Watch Daily and Carl Koppelman Give Names to These 5 Murder Victims | publisher=Fox | work=Crime Watch Daily | date=October 10, 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 [[isotope analysis]] of the decedent's hair and fingernails revealed Buckskin Girl had spent approximately four months in areas within the [[Southwestern United States|Southwestern]] and/or [[Southeastern United States|Southeastern]] United States, as opposed to Ohio, prior to her murder, although the forensic palynology tests had revealed she had most likely originated from either the Northeastern United States or [[Canada]], or had spent a significant amount of time in these regions in the year prior to her murder.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vallieu\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Not From Ohio|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/news/12204/buckskin-girl-not-from-ohio-2|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=WDTN|agency=Troy Daily News|date=July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hollenhorst|first1=John|title=Utah Firm Makes Breakthrough in 1981 Ohio Murder Case|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=40545046&nid=148&title=utah-firm-makes-breakthrough-in-1981-ohio-murder-case|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=KSL|date=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header = \n| width     =\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = Buckskin Girl.jpg\n| width1    = 120\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  = 2011 [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, depicting her distinctive braided hair.\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Photorealistic reconstruction of Buckskin girl .jpg\n| width2    = 120\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  = Additional facial reconstruction of Buckskin Girl, created prior to her 2018 identification as Marcia Lenore King.\n}}\n\n===Link to other murders===\nInitially, investigators speculated to a potential connection between this decedent and the murder of a 27-year-old woman two months earlier, in February 1981, although police never officially linked these two murders.<ref name=no/>\n\nIn 1985, investigators tentatively linked the murder of Buckskin Girl to a nationwide series of murders of caucasian women\u2014several of whom were sex workers or [[erotic dance]]rs\u2014known as the [[Redhead murders|Redhead Murders]]. However, this theory was eventually disproven.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aldrich|first1=Marta W.|title=Officials Puzzle Over String of Redhead Murders|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1985/Officials-Puzzle-Over-String-of-Redhead-Murders/id-8ad8d3ad5b164d3818827a4768931a2c|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=Associated Press|date=April 25, 1985|location=Nashville, Tennessee}}</ref>\n\nSome investigators also speculated that Buckskin Girl may have been the first of numerous young women murdered by a suspected unidentified serial killer who perpetrated his known murders between 1985 and 2004\u2014many of which were of known or suspected prostitutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.websleuths.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=33483&stc=1&d=1367899621|title=Still No Answers|work=The Blade|year=2004}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|These cases were originally linked by a reporter who had discovered similarities among nine nationwide unsolved murders of young women (the majority committed in Ohio).<ref name=uns/>}} This serial killer was suspected to have murdered between seven and ten other young women.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91>{{cite news|title=Investigators of 10 Killings to Meet|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19910315&id=goQcAAAAIBAJ&pg=5900,7506894|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=March 15, 1991}}</ref> All the victims of this suspected serial killer had been murdered via bludgeoning or strangulation, and items of clothing or jewelry were missing from each crime scene.\n\nJewelry and footwear was also missing from the crime scene of Buckskin Girl, and she had been murdered in a similar manner to these victims.<ref name=uns>{{cite web|title=Prostitute Serial Killer|url=http://unsolved.com/archives/prostitute-serial-killer|website=unsolved.com|publisher=[[Unsolved Mysteries]]|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref> However, several elements of evidence were found to contradict this theory. There was no indication Buckskin Girl had engaged in any form of sexual activity prior to her death.<ref name=doe/><ref name=uns/> In addition, unlike many of the victims of this serial killer, she was markedly well-groomed, with a history of dental care.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91/>\n\nIn 1991, a newly-established [[task force]] convened in [[London, Ohio]]. This task force was dedicated to the investigation of these unsolved homicides, which had occurred in Ohio, [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Pennsylvania]] and [[Illinois]] and comprised of investigators from more than a dozen law enforcement agencies.<ref name=pb91/>\n\n==Further forensic analysis==\nWith advances in technology and the increasing use of [[Genetic testing|DNA analysis]] in criminal investigations, investigators were able to extract the decedent's DNA from the blood sample preserved in 1981. This [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]]<ref name=namus/> was added to the growing number of law enforcement databases.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nIn 2001, the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory generated a [[DNA profiling|DNA profile]] of Buckskin Girl,<ref name=\"sossoman\" /> this data was entered into the newly established [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] (NamUs) database in 2008, through which her fingerprints, dental and DNA information were made nationally accessible to law enforcement.<ref name=\"perspectives\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives in Forensic Human Skeletal Identification|editor1=Krista E. Latham|editor2=Eric J. Bartelink|editor3=Michael Finnegan|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=Elsevier, Inc.|isbn=978-0-12-805429-1|pages=124\u2013125|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhdHDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&sig=AUEKTXjtDwA-hpSQptDTfynNu68&ved=0ahUKEwj_k5zNw6bXAhVMwWMKHXCwBxwQ6AEIQjAF#v=onepage&q=NamUS%3A%204790|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> This data was able to concludsively rule out any possibility of 226 missing teenage girls and young women as Buckskin Girl.<ref name=namus/> In 2009, a [[mitochondrial DNA]] sample was submitted to the [[FBI]] for inclusion within the [[Combined DNA Index System]] (CODIS).<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, NamUs case management was assigned to Dr Elizabeth Murray, a [[Cincinnati]] based [[Forensic anthropology|forensic anthropologist]] and professor of biology, who remained involved with the case.<ref name=\"sossoman\" />\n[[File:Buckskin Girl NCMEC.jpg|150px|thumb|upright|[[Forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, created by the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]].]]\n\n===Facial reconstruction===\nIn April 2016, the [[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]] released an updated [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of the victim and added her case to their website, depicting her with and without her braided pigtails.<ref name=\"BGNCMEC\">{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1981|url=http://missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1107106/|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=February 12, 2016|date=February 11, 2016}}</ref> This image was extensively distributed via online media, although initially, no significant leads developed.<ref>{{cite web|title='Buckskin Girl' Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to Identification of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|website=cbsnews.com|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=April 4, 2020|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Pollen analysis===\nIn 2016, the Miami County Police Department approved [[forensic palynology]] testing upon the victim's clothing in their efforts to identify her and her murderer(s). This testing was conducted by the [[United States Border Patrol|U.S. Customs and Border Protection Agency]].<ref name=\"vallieu\"/> The results of this testing suggested Buckskin Girl had either originated within the [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] United States, or had spent a significant amount of time in this region in the year prior to her murder. Her clothing also contained high levels of soot from exposure to vehicular traffic and/or industrial activity, supporting investigators' initial suspicions she may have been a habitual hitchhiker.<ref name=\"kennedy\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Megan|title=Miami Co. Cold Case Heats Up With Facial Reconstruction, Other developments|url=http://wdtn.com/2016/04/27/miami-co-cold-case-heats-up-with-facial-reconstruction-other-developments/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WDTN News|agency=LIN Television Corporation|publisher=Media General|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> In addition, the pollen<ref>{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Greg|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified After Being Found Dead in Ohio 37 Years Ago|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/buckskin-girl-identified-after-being-found-dead-in-ohio-37-years-ago|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=Fox News|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> recovered from her external clothing suggested that, shortly before her murder, she had been in an arid climate such as the [[Western United States|Western]] United States, or northern [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Steve|title=New Developments Could ID 'Jane Doe' Found Dead 35 Years Ago|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/new-developments-could-id-jane-doe-found-dead-35/vDqjK2/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Identification==\nOn April 9, 2018, the Miami Valley Crime Laboratory announced they had identified the decedent as 21-year-old Marcia Lenore King of [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> Her identification had been achieved via DNA analysis conducted by the [[DNA Doe Project]], with assistance from the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forensicmag.com/news/2018/04/buck-skin-girl-case-break-success-new-dna-doe-project|title='Buck Skin Girl' Case Break is Success of New DNA Doe Project|date=April 16, 2018|publisher=Forensic Magazine|author=Seth Augenstein}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/611048/the-brave-new-world-of-genetic-genealogy/|title=The Brave New World of Genetic Genealogy|first=Debbie|last=Kennett|work=MIT Technology Review|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> This organization had been contacted by Dr Murray in 2017, and was able to successfully match a sample of King's DNA to a sample submitted for comparison by a first cousin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/04/golden-state-killer-east-area-rapist-dna-genealogy/559070/|title=How a Genealogy Website Led to the Alleged Golden State Killer|first=Sarah|last=Zhang|date=April 27, 2018|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref>\n\nKing had last been seen by her family in 1980. She had never officially been reported as a [[missing person]], although her family had continued to search for her.<ref name=\"tdn\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/top-stories/39213/buckskin-girl-identified|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=Troy Daily News|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> It is believed King had hitchhiked as the primary means of transportation, as investigators had theorized prior to her identification. She is also known to have had ties with both the [[Pittsburg, Kentucky|Pittsburg]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky]] districts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jane 'Buckskin Girl' Doe Identified After 37 Years|url=https://www.fox19.com/story/37935396/jane-buckskin-girl-doe-identified-after-37-years/|work=[[Fox 19]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|In the hope her daughter would initiate contact, King's mother had both continued to reside at the same house she lived in at the time of her daughter's disappearance, and kept the same phone number, should her daughter either return home or telephone her.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Dana|title=Cold Case Homicide Victim Identified after 37 Years|url=http://www.wdtn.com/news/local-news/cold-case-homicide-victim-identified-after-37-years/1116096993|work=WTDN 2|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nAddressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl, a spokesman for the Miami County Police Department informed all present: \"Law enforcement never forgets. We've had a long journey to [be] where we are today.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eustachewich|first1=Lia|title=Murdered 'Buckskin Girl' Finally Identified 37 Years Later |url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/12/murdered-buckskin-girl-finally-identified-37-years-later/|work=The New York Post|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> This spokesman also emphasized the investigation into King's homicide is ongoing,<ref name=\"miamiID\"/> with the primary focus being upon King's movements in the last month of her life, when when she was known to have been in both Pittsburgh and Louisville.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Nancy|title=Woman in Cold Case Murder Finally Identified 37 Years Later |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/national/woman-cold-case-murder-finally-identified-years-later/5TjPOMWQ3YGPyUUDgdBOMP/|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=April 3, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ongoing investigation===\nIn July 2018, the Miami County Police Department announced they had received further information regarding King's actual whereabouts shortly prior to her death. This information included eyewitness accounts placing her in Louisville, Kentucky, approximately 14 days before her death.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/|title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl': Gets New Headstone With Her Name|date=July 20, 2018|author=Nancy Bowman|work=whiotv}}</ref> Six eyewitnesses have also [[Corroborating evidence|corroborated]] accounts of King also being in Arkansas shortly before her murder. It is believed the reason she had traveled to Ohio may have been due to her suspected involvement with a religious organization.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news |last1=Thomason |first1=Tyler |title=Ohio Cold Case Develops New Timeline, Puts Murder Victim in Arkansas Two Weeks Before Death |url=https://www.fox16.com/news/top-stories/ohio-cold-case-develops-new-timeline-puts-murder-victim-in-arkansas-two-weeks-before-death/1915607781 |accessdate=June 9, 2019 |work=FOX16 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the Miami County Sheriff's Office announced they had been able to further reconstruct King's whereabouts, and relationships, in the two weeks prior to her murder,<ref>{{cite news|title=Forensic Genealogy to Be Used in Miami County Unsolved Homicides|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/forensic-genealogy-used-miami-county-unsolved-homicides/oAl1az1NfGHbopAT29pW3M/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=WHIO|date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> adding that as advances in technology now mean [[Nuclear DNA]] samples can be retrieved from hair samples missing the actual [[hair#Root of the hair|root]], they remained confident hair samples discovered at the crime scene and submitted to a renowned Californian [[Paleogenetics|paleogeneticist]] could yield a Nuclear DNA profile of either her murderer, ar an individual she had been in the company of very shortly before her death.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Addressing these latest developments, Miami County Sheriff Dave Duchalk stated: \"We always have hopes to bring justice for homicide victims and their families. We never have, nor will we ever forget, and will continually work the case and, as new technologies are developed, will review our evidence to learn if it is worth re-submitting.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/79673/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"They were hopeful Marcia was going to come home. However, they are learning at this date that that's not going to happen.\"\n| source = [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]] Sheriff Steve Lord, addressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl. April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 30em\n}}\n\n==Funeral==\nKing had been buried as a Jane Doe at Riverside Cemetery in Miami County, Ohio weeks after her death, with several officers assigned to investigate her murder serving as [[pallbearer]]s at her funeral.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> Following the identification of her body, King's family chose for her to remain buried within this cemetery, with her stepmother, Cindy Sossoman, explaining her family's belief that it had been God's plan that their daughter was to be murdered and to remain unidentified for so long, they believed King was [[Blessing|blessed]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> to have passed away within a community which had shown such consideration and dignity to her while she had remained unidentified.<ref name=sossoman/> Her parents had long since divorced, and her father, John Wesley Sossoman, had remarried, having several children with his second wife, all of whom had long wondered as to King's whereabouts and welfare.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\nOn July 20, 2018, a memorial service for King was held at a chapel in Troy, Ohio. This service was officiated by the Reverend Gregory Simmons. Her new headstone was unveiled at this service.<ref name=sossoman>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> Marcia's father, John, had died on January 5, 2018. Her brother, Daniel King, and half-brother, Jonathan Sossoman, had also died by the time King's identity was discovered.<ref name=\"penwell\" /> Her stepmother and eight other surviving family members replaced the headstone simply reading \"Jane Doe\" with a headstone bearing her actual name at this service, which was attended by over fifty local residents. Describing King's personality, her stepmother described her as a \"very trusting\" young woman, before informing all present: \"Words don't describe the feelings we have for all of you, how you have loved her and taken her in your arms.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowman |first1=Nancy |title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl' Gets New Headstone with Her Name |url=https://www.springfieldnewssun.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=Springfield News-Sun |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Cold case]]\n* [[Crime in Ohio]]\n* [[List of formerly unidentified decedents]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[The Doe Network]]\n* [[Unidentified decedent]]\n* [[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths|Unsolved murders]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Law|Ohio}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{cite book| last = Halber| first = Deborah| title = The Skeleton Crew: How Amateur Sleuths Are Solving America's Coldest Cases| year = 2015| publisher = Simon & Schuster | location = New York| isbn = 978-1-451-65758-6}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Katz|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8na|title=Cold Cases: Famous Unsolved Mysteries, Crimes, and Disappearances in America|year=2010|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Santa Barbara|isbn=978-0-313-37692-4}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Latham| first1 = Krista E.| last2 = Bartelink| first2 = Eric J.| last3 = Finnegan| first3 = Michael| title = New Perspectives in Forensic Human Skeletal Identification| year = 2017| publisher = Academic Press | location = San Diego| isbn = 978-0-128-05429-1}}\n* {{cite book| last = Murray| first = Elizabeth A.| title = Forensic Identification: Putting a Name and Face on Death| year = 2012| publisher = Twenty-First Century Books | location = Minneapolis| isbn = 978-1-467-70139-6}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes| year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9}}\n* {{cite book| last = Pettem| first = Silvia| title = The Long Term Missing: Hope and Help for Families| year = 2017| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | location = Maryland| isbn = 978-1-442-25680-4}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Shoester|first=Maria|title=Forensics in Law Enforcement|year=2006|publisher=[[Nova Science Publishers, Inc.]]|location=New York|isbn=978-1-600-21164-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Marcia King}}\n* [https://www.whio.com/news/crime--law/with-buckskin-girl-investigation-intensifies-into-unsolved-homicide/Fz5capsVOPZknmNAxuYDCP/ Contemporary news article] pertaining to the 2018 forensic identification of Buckskin Girl\n* [[DNA Doe Project]] [https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/ ''webpage''] pertaining to the identification of Buckskin Girl\n* {{Find a Grave|124674061|Marcia King}}\n\n{{Unidentified decedent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Marcia}}\n[[Category:1980s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:1981 in Ohio]]\n[[Category:1981 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Forensic palynology]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Formerly unidentified murder victim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Marcia King\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = File:Marcia King.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| alt                = \n| birth_name         = Marcia Lenore King\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1959|6|9}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Body of 'Buckskin Girl' Found in Ohio in 1981 Identified as Arkansas Woman|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/body-buckskin-girl-found-ohio-1981-identified-arkansas/story?id=54417156|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=[[American Broadcasting Company]]|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| disappeared_date   = Circa 1980<!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]], [[Arkansas]], U.S.<ref name=\"tdn\"/>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1981|04|22|1959|06|09}} <ref name=namus/> <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Homicide]] by [[strangulation]]\n| body_discovered    = April 24, 1981\n| resting_place      = Riverside Cemetery, Troy, Miami County, Ohio\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|39.9660|N|84.3256|W|region:US-OH_type:landmark|display=inline}} (approximate) <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| parents            = Jonathan W. Sossoman\u2020 <br />Bonnie Bryant-King<ref name=\"penwell\">{{cite web |title=Jack W. Sossoman |url=https://www.penwellgabeltopeka.com/Obituary/152633/Jack-Sossoman/Topeka-Kansas |publisher=Penwell-Gabel Home Send Flowers |accessdate=30 August 2018 |date=5 January 2018}}</ref>\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Formerly unidentified victim of homicide\n| height             = {{height|ft=5|in=5|abbr=mos}} (approximate)\n| weight             = \n}}\n\n'''Marcia Lenore Sossoman (King)'''<!-- Use name that the family had inscribed on her gravestone --><ref name=\"sossoman\" /> ({{Birth date|1959|6|9}} \u2013 {{Death date|1981|04|22}}) was a 21-year-old [[Arkansas]] woman who was murdered in April 1981 and whose body was discovered in [[Troy, Ohio]] approximately forty-eight hours after her murder. Her body remained unidentified for 36 years before being identified via [[DNA analysis]] and [[genetic genealogy]] in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> King was the first [[unidentified decedent]] to be identified via this method of [[Forensic science|forensic investigation]].<ref name=\"timeline\" /><ref name=\"miamiID\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Sheriff's Office Identifies 1981 Cold Case Victim|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 11, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her 2018 identification, King was informally known as \"'''Buckskin Girl'''\" and \"'''Miami County [[Jane Doe]]'''\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spain|first1=Jamie|title=37 Years After Young Woman's Mysterious Slaying, She is Finally Identified|url=https://people.com/crime/buckskin-girl-found-dead-ohio-identified-37-year-later/|accessdate=March 22, 2020|work=People|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> The first of these two names is in reference to the distinctive tasseled [[buckskin (leather)|buckskin]] poncho<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> she was wearing at the time of her discovery.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help />\n\nFollowing the identification of her body, Marcia King's family erected a new headstone at her grave in Riverside Cemetery, inscribed with her actual name. The investigation into her murder is ongoing.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\n==Discovery==\nOn April 24, 1981, three young men discovered the body of a young [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] woman in a ditch alongside Greenlee Road in [[Newton Township, Miami County, Ohio|Newton Township]], [[Troy, Ohio|Troy]], Ohio.<ref name=still>{{cite news|title=Victim Still Unidentified|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1904&stc=1&d=1332268098|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 30, 1981}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neil|first1=Helen|title=Amateur Sleuths Restore Identity to the Dead|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Amateur-sleuths-restore-identity-to-the-dead-3219899.php|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=Seattle Post Intelligencer|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref> One of the three men, Greg Bridenbaugh, initially noticed the decedent's distinctive buckskin poncho. Informing one of his companions, Neal Hoffman, to take a look at the coat, Hoffman walked closer to the article of clothing before turning toward Bridenbaugh, stating: \"Oh my God, there's a woman in that coat!\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Buckskin Gril' Identified|url=https://www.tdn-net.com/top-stories/39213/buckskin-girl-identified|accessdate=April 4, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|These members of the public had first noticed the decedent's deerskin poncho lying alongside Greenlee Road before discovering her body.<ref name=\"whio\" />}} The young woman was lying in a [[fetal position]], on her right side, and without shoes or socks.<ref name=\"tdn\" /><ref name=namus>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4790|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/4790|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=7 November 2014|date=10 December 2008}}</ref> These members of the public called police to report their discovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Autopsy===\nThe decedent's body was autopsied on the afternoon of her discovery. The medical examination revealed she had suffered extensive [[Blunt trauma|blunt force trauma]] to the head and neck,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullen|first1=Shannon|title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey?|url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116/|accessdate=March 31, 2020|date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> before she had been strangled to death<ref name=still/> approximately forty-eight hours before her body was discovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buckskin Girl|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/|website=dnadoeproject.org|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In addition, her liver had also been lacerated.<ref name=ramsey>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=Rachelle|title=Jane Doe Doesn't Have a Name or Suspect|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1999&stc=1&d=1348637351|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=August 29, 1994}}</ref> She had not been subjected to any form of [[sexual assault]].<ref name=jim>{{cite news|last1=DeBrosse|first1=Jim|title='Somebody Cares About Them. We Do': Jane Doe Cases Could be Solved 'Overnight' if Database Utilized, Police Say|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/media/news155.html|accessdate=June 1, 2014|newspaper=Dayton Daily News|date=August 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe woman had been between {{cvt|5|ft|4|in|cm}} and {{cvt|5|ft|6|in|cm}} in height, aged between eighteen and twenty-six, and weighed {{convert|125|-|130|lb}}.<ref name=cause/><ref name=id/> She had naturally reddish-brown hair, which was braided into pigtails on both sides of her head.<ref name=doe/><ref name=help/><ref name=id/><ref name=cause>{{cite news|title=Strangulation Cause of Death|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1897&stc=1&d=1332267864|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 27, 1981}}</ref> Her eyes were light brown in color, and she had freckles across her face.<ref name=doe/> In addition, her nose was described as being \"very pointed\".<ref name=watch/> The victim also had a ruddy complexion, indicating she had spent a lot of time outdoors in the final weeks or months of her life.<ref name=doe /><ref name=tri/>\n\nThe young woman had maintained a high level of personal hygiene. All her teeth, including her [[Wisdom tooth|wisdom teeth]], were in good condition and had no evidence of [[Dental restoration|fillings]] or other dental work, except for one porcelain [[Crown (dentistry)|crown]] upon her upper-right [[incisor]].<ref name=namus/><ref name=BGNCMEC/> The coroner also noted several scars upon her body, including a vertical scar beneath her chin, with other scars also visible upon one wrist, both arms, and one ankle.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami>{{cite web |title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981 |url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210190938/http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiCountyJaneDoeApril1981 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |year=2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Clothing===\nThe young woman was dressed in blue bell-bottom [[Wrangler (jeans)|Wrangler]] jeans, a brown turtleneck pullover sweater with an orange crisscross design on the front, a white size 32D bra,<ref name=doe/> and a hoodless deerskin poncho with purple lining, which appeared to be handmade.<ref name=tri>{{cite web|title=Miami County Jane Doe, OH |url=http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414175922/http://meyahna.tripod.com/pg21.html |archivedate=April 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=help>{{cite web|last=Besso |first=Donna |title=Need Help Identifying \"The Buckskin Girl\" |url=http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414195811/http://www.gather.com/viewArticle.action?articleId=281474977406629 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 13, 2014 |date=July 25, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=oh>{{cite web|title=Ohio Unsolved Homicides|url=http://www.ohioattorneygeneral.gov/Files/Law-Enforcement/Investigator/Unidentified-Remains|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> She wore no shoes or socks.<ref name=id>{{cite web|title=Miami Ohio Jane Doe April 1981|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/MiamiOhioJaneDoeApril1981|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> No form of identification was located upon her body or at the crime scene.<ref name=oh/><ref name=miami/>\n\n==Initial investigation==\nBecause the decedent's body was found approximately forty-eight hours after her death,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> police were able to obtain her [[fingerprints]] and dental information. The [[Dental notation|dental charts]] and fingerprints of this decedent yielded no results matching her to any known missing person, and her fingerprints matched no police records, indicating she had no criminal record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> Early police efforts to identify this decedent also involved the creation of a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of her face which was published in local newspapers and broadcast on television networks on April 28, 1981.<ref name=no>{{cite news|title=No identification Yet|url=http://www.officialcoldcaseinvestigations.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=1898&stc=1&d=1332267912|accessdate=September 29, 2015|date=April 28, 1981}}</ref> This initial media publicity surrounding the murder generated approximately two hundred leads. Although all were investigated, all failed to bear fruition.<ref name=still/>\n\nThe victim gradually became known as \"Buckskin Girl\" in reference to the distinctive tasseled buckskin jacket she was wearing when found.<ref name=doe>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=help /><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neill|first1=Helen|title=Volunteers Use Computers to Name the Dead|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/news/2008-03-29-naming-dead_N.htm|accessdate=July 23, 2015|work=USA Today|publisher=Associated Press|date=March 30, 2008}}</ref> The failure to establish her identity hindered investigators' efforts to solve her murder. As her identity remained undiscovered, investigating authorities came to increasingly believe the reason Buckskin Girl remained unidentified had been due to the fact that she had been murdered far from her hometown.<ref name=\"perspectives\" /> A retired investigator is also known to have opined his belief the decedent was highly unlikely to have originated from the area where she was discovered.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nAuthorities strongly believed Buckskin Girl had been murdered elsewhere and her body discarded beside the road shortly after her death.<ref name=no/><ref name=cause/> This conclusion was supported by the fact her bare feet were clean, showing no indication of her having walked upon a dirty surface, and because [[Interstate 75]] is just {{convert|5|mi|0|spell=in}} from where her body was recovered, making the site a convenient and discreet location to discard a body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/news/projects/ourstories/10570633-74/doe-jane-hickey|title=Slain Jane Doe's Curious Case in Ohio Still Puzzles After 35 Years|first=Chris|last=Togneri|date=June 4, 2016|website=TribLIVE.com}}</ref> Police and the media later speculated that she may have been a teenage runaway or a possible victim of a serial killer known to have murdered several sex workers in the region during the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=jim/><ref name=doe/><ref name=tri/> However, her body had not been subjected to any form of sexual assault, indicating she was unlikely to have been a sex worker.<ref name=doe/>\n\nThe investigation into Buckskin Girl's murder gradually became a [[cold case]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Winsor|first1=Morgan|title=Jane Doe No More: Miami County Sheriff IDs Cold Case Victim 37 Years Later|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/miami-county-sheriff-office-release-new-details-1981-unsolved-homicide-case/fmfdENjXMReEHV5VZGPcpI/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=[[WHIO-TV]]|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> although police and other officials continued to investigate her murder. Her clothing and other [[physical evidence]] recovered at the crime scene was retained, and a sample of her blood preserved.<ref name=\"whio\">{{cite news|title=Miami County Authorities Still Working on Jane Doe Case|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425044702/http://www.whio.com/videos/news/miami-county-authorities-still-working-on-jane-doe/vDQhjj/|archive-date=April 25, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Theories==\n===Lifestyle===\nInvestigators theorized that Buckskin Girl had been a runaway teenager, a foster child, or a transient wanderer unlikely to have spent a significant period of time in Ohio prior to her death, although her high quality of personal hygiene strongly indicated that she had not lived as a vagrant.<ref name=doe/> As her body was located close to a town road instead of a highway, the probability of her being a wanderer for a significant amount of time was considered to be negligible.<ref name=watch/> The absence of her footwear at the crime scene led some investigators to believe she may have been murdered by an abusive partner.<ref name=watch>{{cite web | url=http://crimewatchdaily.com/2015/10/19/help-crime-watch-daily-and-carl-koppelman-give-names-to-these-5-murder-victims/ | title=Help Crime Watch Daily and Carl Koppelman Give Names to These 5 Murder Victims | publisher=Fox | work=Crime Watch Daily | date=October 10, 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 [[isotope analysis]] of the decedent's hair and fingernails revealed Buckskin Girl had spent approximately four months in areas within the [[Southwestern United States|Southwestern]] and/or [[Southeastern United States|Southeastern]] United States, as opposed to Ohio, prior to her murder, although the forensic palynology tests had revealed she had most likely originated from either the Northeastern United States or [[Canada]], or had spent a significant amount of time in these regions in the year prior to her murder.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 133UFOH|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/133ufoh.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vallieu\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Not From Ohio|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/news/12204/buckskin-girl-not-from-ohio-2|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=WDTN|agency=Troy Daily News|date=July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hollenhorst|first1=John|title=Utah Firm Makes Breakthrough in 1981 Ohio Murder Case|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=40545046&nid=148&title=utah-firm-makes-breakthrough-in-1981-ohio-murder-case|accessdate=January 28, 2018|work=KSL|date=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| header = \n| width     =\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = Buckskin Girl.jpg\n| width1    = 120\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  = 2011 [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, depicting her distinctive braided hair.\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Photorealistic reconstruction of Buckskin girl .jpg\n| width2    = 120\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  = Additional facial reconstruction of Buckskin Girl, created prior to her 2018 identification as Marcia Lenore King.\n}}\n\n===Link to other murders===\nInitially, investigators speculated to a potential connection between this decedent and the murder of a 27-year-old woman two months earlier, in February 1981, although police never officially linked these two murders.<ref name=no/>\n\nIn 1985, investigators tentatively linked the murder of Buckskin Girl to a nationwide series of murders of caucasian women\u2014several of whom were sex workers or [[erotic dance]]rs\u2014known as the [[Redhead murders|Redhead Murders]]. However, this theory was eventually disproven.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aldrich|first1=Marta W.|title=Officials Puzzle Over String of Redhead Murders|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1985/Officials-Puzzle-Over-String-of-Redhead-Murders/id-8ad8d3ad5b164d3818827a4768931a2c|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=Associated Press|date=April 25, 1985|location=Nashville, Tennessee}}</ref>\n\nSome investigators also speculated that Buckskin Girl may have been the first of numerous young women murdered by a suspected unidentified serial killer who perpetrated his known murders between 1985 and 2004\u2014many of which were of known or suspected prostitutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.websleuths.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=33483&stc=1&d=1367899621|title=Still No Answers|work=The Blade|year=2004}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|These cases were originally linked by a reporter who had discovered similarities among nine nationwide unsolved murders of young women (the majority committed in Ohio).<ref name=uns/>}} This serial killer was suspected to have murdered between seven and ten other young women.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91>{{cite news|title=Investigators of 10 Killings to Meet|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19910315&id=goQcAAAAIBAJ&pg=5900,7506894|accessdate=April 16, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=March 15, 1991}}</ref> All the victims of this suspected serial killer had been murdered via bludgeoning or strangulation, and items of clothing or jewelry were missing from each crime scene.\n\nJewelry and footwear was also missing from the crime scene of Buckskin Girl, and she had been murdered in a similar manner to these victims.<ref name=uns>{{cite web|title=Prostitute Serial Killer|url=http://unsolved.com/archives/prostitute-serial-killer|website=unsolved.com|publisher=[[Unsolved Mysteries]]|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref> However, several elements of evidence were found to contradict this theory. There was no indication Buckskin Girl had engaged in any form of sexual activity prior to her death.<ref name=doe/><ref name=uns/> In addition, unlike many of the victims of this serial killer, she was markedly well-groomed, with a history of dental care.<ref name=uns/><ref name=pb91/>\n\nIn 1991, a newly-established [[task force]] convened in [[London, Ohio]]. This task force was dedicated to the investigation of these unsolved homicides, which had occurred in Ohio, [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Pennsylvania]] and [[Illinois]] and comprised of investigators from more than a dozen law enforcement agencies.<ref name=pb91/>\n\n==Further forensic analysis==\nWith advances in technology and the increasing use of DNA analysis in criminal investigations, investigators were able to extract the decedent's DNA from the blood sample preserved in 1981. This [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]]<ref name=namus/> was added to the growing number of law enforcement databases.<ref name=\"whio\" />\n\nIn 2001, the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory generated a [[DNA profiling|DNA profile]] of Buckskin Girl,<ref name=\"sossoman\" /> this data was entered into the newly established [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] (NamUs) database in 2008, through which her fingerprints, dental and DNA information were made nationally accessible to law enforcement.<ref name=\"perspectives\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives in Forensic Human Skeletal Identification|editor1=Krista E. Latham|editor2=Eric J. Bartelink|editor3=Michael Finnegan|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=Elsevier, Inc.|isbn=978-0-12-805429-1|pages=124\u2013125|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhdHDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&sig=AUEKTXjtDwA-hpSQptDTfynNu68&ved=0ahUKEwj_k5zNw6bXAhVMwWMKHXCwBxwQ6AEIQjAF#v=onepage&q=NamUS%3A%204790|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref> This data was able to concludsively rule out any possibility of 226 missing teenage girls and young women as Buckskin Girl.<ref name=namus/> In 2009, a [[mitochondrial DNA]] sample was submitted to the [[FBI]] for inclusion within the [[Combined DNA Index System]] (CODIS).<ref>{{cite news|title=Buckskin Girl Press Release|url=https://dnadoeproject.org/press-release-for-buckskin-girl/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, NamUs case management was assigned to Dr Elizabeth Murray, a [[Cincinnati]] based [[Forensic anthropology|forensic anthropologist]] and professor of biology, who remained involved with the case.<ref name=\"sossoman\" />\n[[File:Buckskin Girl NCMEC.jpg|150px|thumb|upright|[[Forensic facial reconstruction]] of Buckskin Girl, created by the [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]].]]\n\n===Facial reconstruction===\nIn April 2016, the [[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]] released an updated [[forensic facial reconstruction]] of the victim and added her case to their website, depicting her with and without her braided pigtails.<ref name=\"BGNCMEC\">{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1981|url=http://missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1107106/|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=February 12, 2016|date=February 11, 2016}}</ref> This image was extensively distributed via online media, although initially, no significant leads developed.<ref>{{cite web|title='Buckskin Girl' Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to Identification of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|website=cbsnews.com|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=April 4, 2020|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Pollen analysis===\nIn 2016, the Miami County Police Department approved [[forensic palynology]] testing upon the victim's clothing in their efforts to identify her and her murderer(s). This testing was conducted by the [[United States Border Patrol|U.S. Customs and Border Protection Agency]].<ref name=\"vallieu\"/> The results of this testing suggested Buckskin Girl had either originated within the [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] United States, or had spent a significant amount of time in this region in the year prior to her murder. Her clothing also contained high levels of soot from exposure to vehicular traffic and/or industrial activity, supporting investigators' initial suspicions she may have been a habitual hitchhiker.<ref name=\"kennedy\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Megan|title=Miami Co. Cold Case Heats Up With Facial Reconstruction, Other developments|url=http://wdtn.com/2016/04/27/miami-co-cold-case-heats-up-with-facial-reconstruction-other-developments/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WDTN News|agency=LIN Television Corporation|publisher=Media General|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref> In addition, the pollen<ref>{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Greg|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified After Being Found Dead in Ohio 37 Years Ago|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/buckskin-girl-identified-after-being-found-dead-in-ohio-37-years-ago|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=Fox News|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> recovered from her external clothing suggested that, shortly before her murder, she had been in an arid climate such as the [[Western United States|Western]] United States, or northern [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Steve|title=New Developments Could ID 'Jane Doe' Found Dead 35 Years Ago|url=http://www.whio.com/videos/news/new-developments-could-id-jane-doe-found-dead-35/vDqjK2/|accessdate=April 28, 2016|work=WHIO|publisher=Cox Media Group|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Identification==\nOn April 9, 2018, the Miami Valley Crime Laboratory announced they had identified the decedent as 21-year-old Marcia Lenore King of [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], [[Arkansas]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=\"Buckskin Girl\" Case: DNA Breakthrough Leads to ID of 1981 Murder Victim|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/buckskin-girl-case-groundbreaking-dna-tech-leads-to-id-of-1981-murder-victim/|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=Crimesider|agency=American Broadcasting Company|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> Her identification had been achieved via [[Genetic testing|DNA analysis]] conducted by the [[DNA Doe Project]], with assistance from the Miami Valley Regional Crime Laboratory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forensicmag.com/news/2018/04/buck-skin-girl-case-break-success-new-dna-doe-project|title='Buck Skin Girl' Case Break is Success of New DNA Doe Project|date=April 16, 2018|publisher=Forensic Magazine|author=Seth Augenstein}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/611048/the-brave-new-world-of-genetic-genealogy/|title=The Brave New World of Genetic Genealogy|first=Debbie|last=Kennett|work=MIT Technology Review|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref> This organization had been contacted by Dr Murray in 2017, and was able to successfully match a sample of King's DNA to a sample submitted for comparison by a first cousin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/04/golden-state-killer-east-area-rapist-dna-genealogy/559070/|title=How a Genealogy Website Led to the Alleged Golden State Killer|first=Sarah|last=Zhang|date=April 27, 2018|accessdate=March 29, 2020|work=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref>\n\nKing had last been seen by her family in 1980. She had never officially been reported as a [[missing person]], although her family had continued to search for her.<ref name=\"tdn\">{{cite news|last1=Vallieu|first1=Melody|title='Buckskin Girl' Identified|url=http://www.tdn-net.com/top-stories/39213/buckskin-girl-identified|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=Troy Daily News|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> It is believed King had hitchhiked as the primary means of transportation, as investigators had theorized prior to her identification. She is also known to have had ties with both the [[Pittsburg, Kentucky|Pittsburg]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky]] districts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jane 'Buckskin Girl' Doe Identified After 37 Years|url=https://www.fox19.com/story/37935396/jane-buckskin-girl-doe-identified-after-37-years/|work=[[Fox 19]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|In the hope her daughter would initiate contact, King's mother had both continued to reside at the same house she lived in at the time of her daughter's disappearance, and kept the same phone number, should her daughter either return home or telephone her.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Dana|title=Cold Case Homicide Victim Identified after 37 Years|url=http://www.wdtn.com/news/local-news/cold-case-homicide-victim-identified-after-37-years/1116096993|work=WTDN 2|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nAddressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl, a spokesman for the Miami County Police Department informed all present: \"Law enforcement never forgets. We've had a long journey to [be] where we are today.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eustachewich|first1=Lia|title=Murdered 'Buckskin Girl' Finally Identified 37 Years Later |url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/12/murdered-buckskin-girl-finally-identified-37-years-later/|work=The New York Post|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> This spokesman also emphasized the investigation into King's homicide is ongoing,<ref name=\"miamiID\"/> with the primary focus being upon King's movements in the last month of her life, when when she was known to have been in both Pittsburgh and Louisville.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Nancy|title=Woman in Cold Case Murder Finally Identified 37 Years Later |url=https://www.ajc.com/news/national/woman-cold-case-murder-finally-identified-years-later/5TjPOMWQ3YGPyUUDgdBOMP/|work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|accessdate=April 3, 2020|date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ongoing investigation===\nIn July 2018, the Miami County Police Department announced they had received further information regarding King's actual whereabouts shortly prior to her death. This information included eyewitness accounts placing her in Louisville, Kentucky, approximately 14 days before her death.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/|title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl': Gets New Headstone With Her Name|date=July 20, 2018|author=Nancy Bowman|work=whiotv}}</ref> Six eyewitnesses have also [[Corroborating evidence|corroborated]] accounts of King also being in Arkansas shortly before her murder. It is believed the reason she had traveled to Ohio may have been due to her suspected involvement with a religious organization.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news |last1=Thomason |first1=Tyler |title=Ohio Cold Case Develops New Timeline, Puts Murder Victim in Arkansas Two Weeks Before Death |url=https://www.fox16.com/news/top-stories/ohio-cold-case-develops-new-timeline-puts-murder-victim-in-arkansas-two-weeks-before-death/1915607781 |accessdate=June 9, 2019 |work=FOX16 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the Miami County Sheriff's Office announced they had been able to further reconstruct King's whereabouts, and relationships, in the two weeks prior to her murder,<ref>{{cite news|title=Forensic Genealogy to Be Used in Miami County Unsolved Homicides|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/forensic-genealogy-used-miami-county-unsolved-homicides/oAl1az1NfGHbopAT29pW3M/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|work=WHIO|date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> adding that as advances in technology now mean [[Nuclear DNA]] samples can be retrieved from hair samples missing the actual [[hair#Root of the hair|root]], they remained confident hair samples discovered at the crime scene and submitted to a renowned Californian [[Paleogenetics|paleogeneticist]] could yield a Nuclear DNA profile of either her murderer, ar an individual she had been in the company of very shortly before her death.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://codingsocieties.com/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case-troy-daily-news/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Addressing these latest developments, Miami County Sheriff Dave Duchalk stated: \"We always have hopes to bring justice for homicide victims and their families. We never have, nor will we ever forget, and will continually work the case and, as new technologies are developed, will review our evidence to learn if it is worth re-submitting.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New Technology Being Used in 'Buckskin Girl' Case|url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/79673/new-technology-being-used-in-buckskin-girl-case|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"They were hopeful Marcia was going to come home. However, they are learning at this date that that's not going to happen.\"\n| source = [[Miami County, Ohio|Miami County]] Sheriff Steve Lord, addressing the media to announce the formal identification of Buckskin Girl. April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=After 37 Years, Murder Victim Buckskin Girl Has Her Name Back|url=https://torontosun.com/news/world/crime-hunter-after-37-years-murder-victim-buckskin-girl-has-her-name-back|accessdate=March 26, 2020|date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 30em\n}}\n\n==Funeral==\nKing had been buried as a Jane Doe at Riverside Cemetery in Miami County, Ohio weeks after her death, with several officers assigned to investigate her murder serving as [[pallbearer]]s at her funeral.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mullen |first1=Shannon |title=Was Strangled 'Buckskin Girl' from New Jersey? |url=https://eu.app.com/story/news/crime/jersey-mayhem/cold-cases/2016/04/29/buckskin-girl-murder-pollen-nj/83707116 |accessdate=March 27, 2020|publisher=USA Today |date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> Following the identification of her body, King's family chose for her to remain buried within this cemetery, with her stepmother, Cindy Sossoman, explaining her family's belief that it had been God's plan that their daughter was to be murdered and to remain unidentified for so long, they believed King was [[Blessing|blessed]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> to have passed away within a community which had shown such consideration and dignity to her while she had remained unidentified.<ref name=sossoman/> Her parents had long since divorced, and her father, John Wesley Sossoman, had remarried, having several children with his second wife, all of whom had long wondered as to King's whereabouts and welfare.<ref name=sossoman/>\n\nOn July 20, 2018, a memorial service for King was held at a chapel in Troy, Ohio. This service was officiated by the Reverend Gregory Simmons. Her new headstone was unveiled at this service.<ref name=sossoman>{{cite news |last1=Ullery |first1=Michael |title=Sossoman Given Back Her Name |url=https://www.tdn-net.com/news/44910/sossoman-given-back-her-name |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=Troy Daily News |publisher=AIM Media Midwest |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref> Marcia's father, John, had died on January 5, 2018. Her brother, Daniel King, and half-brother, Jonathan Sossoman, had also died by the time King's identity was discovered.<ref name=\"penwell\" /> Her stepmother and eight other surviving family members replaced the headstone simply reading \"Jane Doe\" with a headstone bearing her actual name at this service, which was attended by over fifty local residents. Describing King's personality, her stepmother described her as a \"very trusting\" young woman, before informing all present: \"Words don't describe the feelings we have for all of you, how you have loved her and taken her in your arms.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowman |first1=Nancy |title=Gravesite for 'Buckskin Girl' Gets New Headstone with Her Name |url=https://www.springfieldnewssun.com/news/local/buckskin-girl-grave-troy-get-new-headstone-with-her-name/nNQOsP1P8P4v40J6byXJvN/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=Springfield News-Sun |date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Cold case]]\n* [[Crime in Ohio]]\n* [[List of formerly unidentified decedents]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[The Doe Network]]\n* [[Unidentified decedent]]\n* [[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths|Unsolved murders]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1980s|Law|Ohio}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{cite book| last = Halber| first = Deborah| title = The Skeleton Crew: How Amateur Sleuths Are Solving America's Coldest Cases| year = 2015| publisher = Simon & Schuster | location = New York| isbn = 978-1-451-65758-6}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Katz|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8na|title=Cold Cases: Famous Unsolved Mysteries, Crimes, and Disappearances in America|year=2010|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Santa Barbara|isbn=978-0-313-37692-4}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Latham| first1 = Krista E.| last2 = Bartelink| first2 = Eric J.| last3 = Finnegan| first3 = Michael| title = New Perspectives in Forensic Human Skeletal Identification| year = 2017| publisher = Academic Press | location = San Diego| isbn = 978-0-128-05429-1}}\n* {{cite book| last = Murray| first = Elizabeth A.| title = Forensic Identification: Putting a Name and Face on Death| year = 2012| publisher = Twenty-First Century Books | location = Minneapolis| isbn = 978-1-467-70139-6}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes| year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9}}\n* {{cite book| last = Pettem| first = Silvia| title = The Long Term Missing: Hope and Help for Families| year = 2017| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | location = Maryland| isbn = 978-1-442-25680-4}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Shoester|first=Maria|title=Forensics in Law Enforcement|year=2006|publisher=[[Nova Science Publishers, Inc.]]|location=New York|isbn=978-1-600-21164-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Marcia King}}\n* [https://www.whio.com/news/crime--law/with-buckskin-girl-investigation-intensifies-into-unsolved-homicide/Fz5capsVOPZknmNAxuYDCP/ Contemporary news article] pertaining to the 2018 forensic identification of Buckskin Girl\n* [[DNA Doe Project]] [https://dnadoeproject.org/case/buckskin-girl/ ''webpage''] pertaining to the identification of Buckskin Girl\n* {{Find a Grave|124674061|Marcia King}}\n\n{{Unidentified decedent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Marcia}}\n[[Category:1980s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:1981 in Ohio]]\n[[Category:1981 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Forensic palynology]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against women]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Kieronoldham", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move links to first instance of mention.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Marcia_King"}
{"title_page": "Vocational panel", "text_new": "A '''vocational panel''' ({{lang-ga|rolla gairm bheatha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Olltoghch\u00e1n an tSeanaid, 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/ga/election-results/seanad-general-election-2020/ |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=ga |date=3 April 2020 |quote=Foilseofar na tortha\u00ed comhairimh is d\u00e9ana\u00ed do na c\u00faig rolla gairm bheatha anseo d\u00edreach tar \u00e9is toradh gach comhairimh a fh\u00f3gairt.}}</ref>) is any of five lists of candidates from which are elected a total of 43 of the 60{{#tag:ref|Of the other 17 senators, 6 are elected from [[University constituency|university constituencies]] and [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|11 are appointed]] by the [[Taoiseach]] ([[prime minister]]).|group=\"n\"}} senators in [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], the [[upper house]] of the [[Oireachtas]] ([[parliament]]) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. Each panel corresponds to a grouping of \"interests and services\" ([[profession]]s or [[vocation]]s) of which candidates are required to have \"knowledge and practical experience\". The panels are nominated partly by Oireachtas members and partly by vocational organisations. From each panel, between five and eleven senators are [[Indirect election|elected indirectly]], by Oireachtas members and local councillors, using the [[single transferable vote]]. The broad requirements are specified by Article 18 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and the implementation details by [[Acts of the Oireachtas]], principally the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, and associated [[statutory instrument]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement, Amendments, SIs made under the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/isbc/1947_42.html |website=Irish Statute Book |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interests and services, and subpanels==\nArticle 18.7.1\u00b0 of the Constitution defines the five panels and specifies that each shall elect between five and eleven senators. The 1947 Act defines the numbers of senators to be elected from each of the panels, and also provides for the division of each panel into two sub-panels: the nominating bodies sub-panel and the Oireachtas sub-panel, with a minimum number from each sub-panel.\t \n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Senate vocational panels\n!rowspan=2|Panel\n!colspan=2|Senators\n!colspan=2|Nominating bodies (as of 2020)\n!rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|\"Interests and services\" represented<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/3/enacted/en/html#sec3 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.3]</ref>\n|-\n!Total  !!Min. per<br/>sub-panel\n!Number<ref>{{cite web |title=Register of Nominating Bodies as revised at the annual revision and signed by the Seanad Returning Officer in pursuance of section 19 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended. |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/nominatingBodies/seanad/2019/2019-07-24_register-of-nominating-bodies-2019_en.pdf |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n!Max nominees<br/>per body<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/7/enacted/en/html s.26(2) of the 1947 act as amended by s.7 of the 1954 act]</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Administrative Panel|Administrative]]\n| 7  || 3\n| 20 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Public administration and social services, including voluntary social activities\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Agricultural Panel|Agricultural]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 10 || 2\n|align=\"left\"| \"Agriculture and allied interests, and fisheries\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cultural and Educational Panel|Cultural and Educational]]\n| 5  || 2\n| 34 || 1 \n|align=\"left\"| \"The national language {{bracket|i.e. [[Irish language|Irish]]}} and culture, literature, art, education\" and \"such [[profession]]al interests as may be defined by law\", namely \"law\" and \"medicine, including surgery, dentistry, veterinary medicine, and pharmaceutical chemistry\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Industrial and Commercial Panel|Industrial and Commercial]]\n| 9  || 3\n| 47 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Industry and commerce, including banking, finance, accountancy, engineering, and architecture\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Labour Panel|Labour]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 2  || 7\n|align=\"left\"| \"Labour, whether [[trade union|organised]] or unorganised\"\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Total\n| 43  || \u2014\n| 113 || \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Nominations==\nCandidates must be Irish citizens over the age of 21. Candidates can be nominated by two methods: by Oireachtas members or by nominating bodies. Nominating bodies are organisations that are connected to the particular vocation, for example, the [[Irish Congress of Trade Unions]] can nominate in the Labour panel, and the [[Royal Irish Academy]] can nominate in the Cultural and Education panel.\n\nAs the electorate is restricted to elected councillors, [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s and senators, the political parties have a great influence in the nomination procedures. The main political parties are aware of how many seats they will win after the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]] election and will endorse candidates that they deem to have a chance of election to the D\u00e1il in the next general election. The nominating bodies tend to nominate party members. Even where non-party candidates get on the ballot paper, it is very rare that these candidates are successful.\n\n===<!-- [[Completion of panels]] redirects here-->Completion of panels===\nThe minimum number of nominees for each subpanel is two plus the maximum number to be elected from the subpanel. If there are too few candidates on a subpanel, the [[Taoiseach]] must nominate extra candidates to \"complete\" the panel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.37 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/37/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[21st Seanad|1997 Seanad election]], [[Bertie Ahern]] was obliged to nominate four candidates across three Oireachtas sub-panels, none of whom polled well in the ensuing election.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Coakley |first1=John |last2=Manning |first2=Maurice |editor-last1=Marsh |editor-first1=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 1997 |chapter=The Senate Elections ||date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-96854-9 |page=203 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwDFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA203 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|nomination directly to the Seanad]] must be by a Taoiseach elected after a [[D\u00e1il election results|D\u00e1il general election]], nomination of candidates to complete a panel may be by an ''acting'' Taoiseach. For example, in 2020 [[Leo Varadkar]] was acting Taoiseach after [[2020 Irish general election|the D\u00e1il election]]; in [[2020 Irish Seanad election|the ensuing Seanad election]], Oireachtas members only nominated eight candidates to their subpanel of the Labour panel, so Varadkar nominated one more to bring the total up to the minimum of nine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panels of candidates prepared by the Seanad Returning Officer pursuant to Section 43 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954. |journal=Iris Oifigi\u00fail |date=10 March 2020 |issue=20A [Supplement] |page=6 |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/electoralRoll/seanad/2020/2020-03-10_seanad-general-election-2020-panels-of-candidates_en.pdf#page=6}}; {{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=FG\u2019s Mary Seery Kearney added to ticket to contest Seanad election |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fg-s-mary-seery-kearney-added-to-ticket-to-contest-seanad-election-1.4198771 |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voting==\nIn all panel elections [[postal voting]] is used. The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad is the [[returning officer]] of the count, during which each ballot is given the value of 1,000 to aid the transfer of fractions of votes. The [[electoral college]] is the same for all of the vocational panels but varies between general and [[by-election]]s. \n\nAt a Seanad general election the voters are members of [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|city and county councils]], the newly elected D\u00e1il and the outgoing Seanad; {{as of|2020|lc=y}} these number 949, 160, and 60 respectively, discounting any vacancies.{{#tag:ref|Typically, some local councillors and members of the old Seanad will have just been elected to the new D\u00e1il, vacating their former seats. In the case of a senator nominated by a Taoiseach, the outgoing acting Taoiseach will nominate a replacement in time for the panel election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=Former Labour TDs to compete for Seanad seats Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in in competition with outgoing senators for nomination |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/former-labour-tds-to-compete-for-seanad-seats-1.2571697 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> Typically, local councils likewise co-opt replacements in time,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Rachel |title=Rush to fill vacant seats created by councillors elected to D\u00e1il |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2016/0314/Pg002.html#Ar00203 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irush Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> but no by-elections are held to replace outgoing panel or university senators.|group=\"n\"}} At a by-election the voters are the current members of the D\u00e1il and Seanad.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(8) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act], and [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/69/enacted/en/html#sec69 s.69]</ref>\n\nAt a general election each panel is elected separately, the ballot listing nominees from both subpanels collated together in alphabetical order of surname. Voting is by the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), with the modification that a minimum number from each subpanel must be elected.\n\nBy-elections to fill a casual vacancy use [[instant runoff voting]]; if there are multiple vacancies on the same subpanel, separate parallel by-elections are held instead of a single multiple-seat STV by-election.<ref>1947 act s.58</ref> By-election nominations are from the same subpanel as the departed senator; no body can nominate multiple candidates.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(1)(b) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act]</ref> A by-election must be called within 180 days of a vacancy arising.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/56/enacted/en/html Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.56(1)]</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nIn practice, the vocational element is largely notional. Seanad standing orders make no distinction between senators elected from a panel and other senators, or among different panels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing Orders relative to Public Business |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/parliamentaryBusiness/standingOrders/seanad/2017/2017-09-29_seanad-eireann-standing-orders-relative-to-public-business-2017_en.pdf |publisher=Seanad \u00c9ireann |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=2017}}</ref> For example, of the four senators on the Oireachtas joint committee on Agriculture, Food and the Marine in 2017, only one had been elected from the Agricultural Panel; two were from other panels, while the fourth was a Taoiseach's nominee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Agriculture Committee to discuss tillage and malt industries |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20171016-agriculture-committee-to-discuss-tillage-and-malt-industries/ |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=16 October 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Names Of The Members Nominated And Of The Members Elected |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2016-06-08/5/ |website=Seanad \u00c9ireann (25th Seanad) debates |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=8 June 2016}}</ref> The fact that the electorate is composed mainly of officials elected in party-political elections means the candidates they favour are also party-political rather than vocationally oriented.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\">{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Mary C. |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2016: The Election that Nobody Won |date=2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9783319408880 |pages=227\u2013253 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKVlDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227  |chapter=The Seanad Election: Second Chamber, Second Chance |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-40889-7_10}}</ref> Candidates from the \"outside\" (nominating bodies) panel tend to win the minimum number of seats on each panel; those elected are also mainly party based.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> Since the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 recession]] there has been an increased proportion of [[independent politician]]s elected at local and D\u00e1il elections, which in turn has led to some independent senators returned from the panel elections;<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> some but not all of these have a greater focus on the functional areas of their panel.\n\n==History==\nThe vocational aspect of the Seanad's constitution was a reflection of the influence of [[corporatism]] on [[Catholic social teaching]] of the 1930s, as outlined in the encyclical ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]''. This in turn influenced [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]'s thinking during the [[Adoption of the Constitution of Ireland|drafting of the 1937 Constitution]].<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\">{{cite book |first1=Martin |last1=O'Donoghue |title=Reforming Senates: Upper Legislative Houses in North Atlantic Small Powers 1800\u2013present |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |series=Routledge Studies in Modern History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2fS2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |isbn=9780367339685 |pages=204\u2013214 |chapter=Vocational voices or puppets of the Lower House? Irish senators, 1938-1948.}}</ref> The place of the Seanad in the new constitution was first discussed by a 1936 commission, which produced a majority and minority report, with dissenters from both.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+1936 Second House of the Oireachtas Commission recommendations<ref name=\"DL056798\">{{cite book |url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056798.pdf#page=11 |author=Second House of the Oireachtas Commission |date=November 1936 |series=Official publications |volume=P.2475 |title=Report |nopp=y |pages=Chapter III [majority report] pp.9\u201311, \u00a7\u00a717, 21\u201325; Chapter X [minority report] pp.30\u201333, \u00a7\u00a714\u201317 |location=Dublin |publisher=Stationery Office |oclc=863521464}}</ref>\n|-\n! Report \n! Fraction elected \n! Electors\n! Sectors of interest\n! Nominators\n|-\n! Majority\n| 30 of 45\n| D\u00e1il election candidates, [[Weighted voting|weighted]] by first-preference vote\n| \"National Language and Culture, the Arts, Agriculture (in all its forms) and Fisheries, Industry and Commerce, Finance, Health and Social Welfare, Foreign Affairs, Education, Law, Labour, Public Administration (including Town and Country Planning).\"\n| Nominating committee elected by D\u00e1il members using proportional representation\n|-\n! Minority\n| 40 of 50\n| [[Teachta D\u00e1la|D\u00e1il members]]\n| \"(1) Farming and Fisheries, (2) Labour, (3) Industry and Commerce, (4) Education and the learned Professions.\"\n| Largely by specified functional organisations; partly by the relevant government minister.\n|}\n\nDe Valera's 1937 Seanad took more from the minority report.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/> The original electoral method differed in several ways from that used since 1947:<ref name=\"Byrne2013\">{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Elaine |title=Past Reforms and Present Policy: examining the Seanad Electoral(Panel Members) Act, 1947 |url=http://historyhub.ie/past-reforms-present-policy |website=History Hub |publisher=University College Dublin |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* There was a single STV ballot paper listing all candidates for all panels in order of surname.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/40/enacted/en/html#sec40 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.40(1)]</ref> The requirement for specific numbers of winners from each of five panels (and ten sub-panels) was preserved, greatly complicating the task for voters filling in the large ballot, and for eliminating candidates during the STV count process.\n* Instead of all county councillors voting directly for the panel, each council elected seven of its members to act as \"electors\".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/37/enacted/en/html#sec37 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.37]</ref>\n\nFor the [[Members of the 2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]], there were only 330 voters (24 of the 354 electors boycotted) which in a 43-seat ballot gave a quota of just eight votes to be elected.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> There were rumours of [[vote buying]] after the first three Seanad election and finally two convictions after the [[Members of the 5th Seanad|1944 Seanad election]].<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> The Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 was therefore repealed and replaced by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, which is still in force with minor amendments.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1969 French constitutional referendum]] \u2014 rejected proposal to merge the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council|Economic, Social and Environmental Council]] into the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n* [[Functional constituency]] \u2014 in Hong Kong and Macao\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |title=Constitution of Ireland |pages=Articles 18\u201319 |nopp=y |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article18 |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947  |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/enacted/en/index.html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/publications/?author=seanad-eireann&topic%5B0%5D=election-results&topic%5B1%5D=elections Seanad election details since 2002], Oireachtas website\n\n{{Seanad \u00c9ireann}}\n\n[[Category:Seanad constituencies]]\n[[Category:Corporatism]]\n[[Category:Local authorities in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "A '''vocational panel''' ({{lang-ga|rolla gairm bheatha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Olltoghch\u00e1n an tSeanaid, 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/ga/election-results/seanad-general-election-2020/ |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=ga |date=3 April 2020 |quote=Foilseofar na tortha\u00ed comhairimh is d\u00e9ana\u00ed do na c\u00faig rolla gairm bheatha anseo d\u00edreach tar \u00e9is toradh gach comhairimh a fh\u00f3gairt.}}</ref>) is any of five lists of candidates from which are elected a total of 43 of the 60{{#tag:ref|Of the other 17 senators, 6 are elected from [[University constituency|university constituencies]] and [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|11 are appointed]] by the [[Taoiseach]] ([[prime minister]]).|group=\"n\"}} senators in [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], the [[upper house]] of the [[Oireachtas]] ([[parliament]]) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. Each panel corresponds to a grouping of \"interests and services\" ([[profession]]s or [[vocation]]s) of which candidates are required to have \"knowledge and practical experience\". The panels are nominated partly by Oireachtas members and partly by vocational organisations. From each panel, between five and eleven senators are [[Indirect election|elected indirectly]], by Oireachtas members and local councillors, using the [[single transferable vote]]. The broad requirements are specified by Article 18 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and the implementation details by [[Acts of the Oireachtas]], principally the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, and associated [[statutory instrument]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement, Amendments, SIs made under the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/isbc/1947_42.html |website=Irish Statute Book |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interests and services, and subpanels==\nArticle 18.7.1\u00b0 of the Constitution defines the five panels and specifies that each shall elect between five and eleven senators. The 1947 Act defines the numbers of senators to be elected from each of the panels, and also provides for the division of each panel into two sub-panels: the nominating bodies sub-panel and the Oireachtas sub-panel, with a minimum number from each sub-panel.\t \n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Senate vocational panels\n!rowspan=2|Panel\n!colspan=2|Senators\n!colspan=2|Nominating bodies (as of 2020)\n!rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|\"Interests and services\" represented<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/3/enacted/en/html#sec3 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.3]</ref>\n|-\n!Total  !!Min. per<br/>sub-panel\n!Number<ref>{{cite web |title=Register of Nominating Bodies as revised at the annual revision and signed by the Seanad Returning Officer in pursuance of section 19 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended. |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/nominatingBodies/seanad/2019/2019-07-24_register-of-nominating-bodies-2019_en.pdf |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n!Max nominees<br/>per body<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/7/enacted/en/html s.26(2) of the 1947 act as amended by s.7 of the 1954 act]</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Administrative Panel|Administrative]]\n| 7  || 3\n| 20 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Public administration and social services, including voluntary social activities\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Agricultural Panel|Agricultural]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 10 || 2\n|align=\"left\"| \"Agriculture and allied interests, and fisheries\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cultural and Educational Panel|Cultural and Educational]]\n| 5  || 2\n| 34 || 1 \n|align=\"left\"| \"The national language {{bracket|i.e. [[Irish language|Irish]]}} and culture, literature, art, education\" and \"such [[profession]]al interests as may be defined by law\", namely \"law\" and \"medicine, including surgery, dentistry, veterinary medicine, and pharmaceutical chemistry\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Industrial and Commercial Panel|Industrial and Commercial]]\n| 9  || 3\n| 47 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Industry and commerce, including banking, finance, accountancy, engineering, and architecture\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Labour Panel|Labour]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 2  || 7\n|align=\"left\"| \"Labour, whether [[trade union|organised]] or unorganised\"\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Total\n| 43  || \u2014\n| 113 || \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Nominations==\nCandidates must be Irish citizens over the age of 21. Candidates can be nominated by two methods: by Oireachtas members or by nominating bodies. Nominating bodies are organisations that are connected to the particular vocation, for example, the [[Irish Congress of Trade Unions]] can nominate in the Labour panel, and the [[Royal Irish Academy]] can nominate in the Cultural and Education panel.\n\nAs the electorate is restricted to elected councillors, [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s and senators, the political parties have a great influence in the nomination procedures. The main political parties are aware of how many seats they will win after the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]] election and will endorse candidates that they deem to have a chance of election to the D\u00e1il in the next general election. The nominating bodies tend to nominate party members. Even where non-party candidates get on the ballot paper, it is very rare that these candidates are successful.\n\n===<!-- [[Completion of panels]] redirects here-->Completion of panels===\nThe minimum number of nominees for each subpanel is two plus the maximum number to be elected from the subpanel. If there are too few candidates on a subpanel, the [[Taoiseach]] must nominate extra candidates to \"complete\" the panel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.37 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/37/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[21st Seanad|1997 Seanad election]], [[Bertie Ahern]] was obliged to nominate four candidates across three Oireachtas sub-panels, none of whom polled well in the ensuing election.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Coakley |first1=John |last2=Manning |first2=Maurice |editor-last1=Marsh |editor-first1=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 1997 |chapter=The Senate Elections ||date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-96854-9 |page=203 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwDFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA203 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|nomination directly to the Seanad]] must be by a Taoiseach elected after a [[D\u00e1il election results|D\u00e1il general election]], nomination of candidates to complete a panel may be by an ''acting'' Taoiseach. For example, in 2020 [[Leo Varadkar]] was acting Taoiseach after [[2020 Irish general election|the D\u00e1il election]]; in [[2020 Irish Seanad election|the ensuing Seanad election]], Oireachtas members only nominated eight candidates to their subpanel of the Labour panel, so Varadkar nominated one more to bring the total up to the minimum of nine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panels of candidates prepared by the Seanad Returning Officer pursuant to Section 43 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954. |journal=Iris Oifigi\u00fail |date=10 March 2020 |issue=20A [Supplement] |page=6 |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/electoralRoll/seanad/2020/2020-03-10_seanad-general-election-2020-panels-of-candidates_en.pdf#page=6}}; {{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=FG\u2019s Mary Seery Kearney added to ticket to contest Seanad election |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fg-s-mary-seery-kearney-added-to-ticket-to-contest-seanad-election-1.4198771 |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voting==\nIn all panel elections [[postal voting]] is used. The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad is the [[returning officer]] of the count, during which each ballot is given the value of 1,000 to aid the transfer of fractions of votes. The [[electoral college]] is the same for all of the vocational panels but varies between general and [[by-election]]s. \n\nAt a Seanad general election the voters are members of [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|city and county councils]], the newly elected D\u00e1il and the outgoing Seanad; {{as of|2020|lc=y}} these number 949, 160, and 60 respectively, discounting any vacancies.{{#tag:ref|Typically, some local councillors and members of the old Seanad will have just been elected to the new D\u00e1il, vacating their former seats. In the case of a senator nominated by a Taoiseach, the outgoing acting Taoiseach will nominate a replacement in time for the panel election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=Former Labour TDs to compete for Seanad seats Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in in competition with outgoing senators for nomination |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/former-labour-tds-to-compete-for-seanad-seats-1.2571697 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> Typically, local councils likewise co-opt replacements in time,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Rachel |title=Rush to fill vacant seats created by councillors elected to D\u00e1il |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2016/0314/Pg002.html#Ar00203 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irush Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> but no by-elections are held to replace outgoing panel or university senators.|group=\"n\"}} At a by-election the voters are the current members of the D\u00e1il and Seanad.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(8) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act], and [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/69/enacted/en/html#sec69 s.69]</ref>\n\nAt a general election each panel is elected separately, the ballot listing nominees from both subpanels collated together in alphabetical order of surname. Voting is by the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), with the modification that a minimum number from each subpanel must be elected.\n\nBy-elections to fill a casual vacancy use [[instant runoff voting]]; if there are multiple vacancies on the same subpanel, separate parallel by-elections are held instead of a single multiple-seat STV by-election.<ref>1947 act s.58</ref> By-election nominations are from the same subpanel as the departed senator; no body can nominate multiple candidates.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(1)(b) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act]</ref> A by-election must be called within 180 days of a vacancy arising.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/56/enacted/en/html Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.56(1)]</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nIn practice, the vocational element is largely notional. Seanad standing orders make no distinction between senators elected from a panel and other senators, or among different panels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing Orders relative to Public Business |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/parliamentaryBusiness/standingOrders/seanad/2017/2017-09-29_seanad-eireann-standing-orders-relative-to-public-business-2017_en.pdf |publisher=Seanad \u00c9ireann |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=2017}}</ref> For example, of the four senators on the Oireachtas joint committee on Agriculture, Food and the Marine in 2017, only one had been elected from the Agricultural Panel; two were from other panels, while the fourth was a Taoiseach's nominee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Agriculture Committee to discuss tillage and malt industries |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20171016-agriculture-committee-to-discuss-tillage-and-malt-industries/ |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=16 October 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Names Of The Members Nominated And Of The Members Elected |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2016-06-08/5/ |website=Seanad \u00c9ireann (25th Seanad) debates |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=8 June 2016}}</ref> The fact that the electorate is composed mainly of officials elected in party-political elections means the candidates they favour are also party-political rather than vocationally oriented.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\">{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Mary C. |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2016: The Election that Nobody Won |date=2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9783319408880 |pages=227\u2013253 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKVlDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227  |chapter=The Seanad Election: Second Chamber, Second Chance |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-40889-7_10}}</ref> Candidates from the \"outside\" (nominating bodies) panel tend to win the minimum number of seats on each panel; those elected are also mainly party based.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> Since the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 recession]] there has been an increased proportion of [[independent politician]]s elected at local and D\u00e1il elections, which in turn has led to some independent senators returned from the panel elections;<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> some but not all of these have a greater focus on the functional areas of their panel.\n\n==History==\nThe vocational aspect of the Seanad's constitution was a reflection of the influence of [[corporatism]] on [[Catholic social teaching]] of the 1930s, as outlined in the encyclical ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]''. This in turn influenced [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]'s thinking during the [[Adoption of the Constitution of Ireland|drafting of the 1937 Constitution]].<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=O'Donoghue |title=Reforming Senates: Upper Legislative Houses in North Atlantic Small Powers 1800\u2013present |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |series=Routledge Studies in Modern History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2fS2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |isbn=9780367339685 |pages=204\u2013214 |chapter=Vocational voices or puppets of the Lower House? Irish senators, 1938-1948.}}</ref> The place of the Seanad in the new constitution was first discussed by a 1936 commission, which produced a majority and minority report, with dissenters from both.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+1936 Second House of the Oireachtas Commission recommendations<ref name=\"DL056798\">{{cite book |url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056798.pdf#page=11 |author=Second House of the Oireachtas Commission |date=November 1936 |series=Official publications |volume=P.2475 |title=Report |nopp=y |pages=Chapter III [majority report] pp.9\u201311, \u00a7\u00a717, 21\u201325; Chapter X [minority report] pp.30\u201333, \u00a7\u00a714\u201317 |location=Dublin |publisher=Stationery Office |oclc=863521464}}</ref>\n|-\n! Report \n! Fraction elected \n! Electors\n! Sectors of interest\n! Nominators\n|-\n! Majority\n| 30 of 45\n| D\u00e1il election candidates, [[Weighted voting|weighted]] by first-preference vote\n| \"National Language and Culture, the Arts, Agriculture (in all its forms) and Fisheries, Industry and Commerce, Finance, Health and Social Welfare, Foreign Affairs, Education, Law, Labour, Public Administration (including Town and Country Planning).\"\n| Nominating committee elected by D\u00e1il members using proportional representation\n|-\n! Minority\n| 40 of 50\n| [[Teachta D\u00e1la|D\u00e1il members]]\n| \"(1) Farming and Fisheries, (2) Labour, (3) Industry and Commerce, (4) Education and the learned Professions.\"\n| Largely by specified functional organisations; partly by the relevant government minister.\n|}\n\nDe Valera's 1937 Seanad took more from the minority report.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/> The original electoral method differed in several ways from that used since 1947:<ref name=\"Byrne2013\">{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Elaine |title=Past Reforms and Present Policy: examining the Seanad Electoral(Panel Members) Act, 1947 |url=http://historyhub.ie/past-reforms-present-policy |website=History Hub |publisher=University College Dublin |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* There was a single STV ballot paper listing all candidates for all panels in order of surname.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/40/enacted/en/html#sec40 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.40(1)]</ref> The requirement for specific numbers of winners from each of five panels (and ten sub-panels) was preserved, greatly complicating the task for voters filling in the large ballot, and for eliminating candidates during the STV count process.\n* Instead of all county councillors voting directly for the panel, each council elected seven of its members to act as \"electors\".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/37/enacted/en/html#sec37 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.37]</ref>\n\nFor the [[Members of the 2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]], there were only 330 voters (24 of the 354 electors boycotted) which in a 43-seat ballot gave a quota of just eight votes to be elected.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> There were rumours of [[vote buying]] after the first three Seanad election and finally two convictions after the [[Members of the 5th Seanad|1944 Seanad election]].<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> The Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 was therefore repealed and replaced by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, which is still in force with minor amendments.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1969 French constitutional referendum]] \u2014 rejected proposal to merge the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council|Economic, Social and Environmental Council]] into the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n* [[Functional constituency]] \u2014 in Hong Kong and Macao\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |title=Constitution of Ireland |pages=Articles 18\u201319 |nopp=y |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article18 |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947  |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/enacted/en/index.html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/publications/?author=seanad-eireann&topic%5B0%5D=election-results&topic%5B1%5D=elections Seanad election details since 2002], Oireachtas website\n\n{{Seanad \u00c9ireann}}\n\n[[Category:Seanad constituencies]]\n[[Category:Corporatism]]\n[[Category:Local authorities in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Jnestorius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:first1=Martin |last1=O'Donoghueq", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vocational_panel"}
{"title_page": "Lou\u017en\u00e1", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = \n| subdivision_name2               = [[Klatovy District|Klatovy]]\n| website                         = http://www.obecmysliv.cz/\n| postal_code                     = 341 01\n| postal_code_type                = Postal&nbsp;code\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_total                = 46\n| elevation_m                     = 553\n| area_total_km2                  = 3.59\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Plze\u0148 Region|Plze\u0148]]\n| settlement_type                 = Village\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{CZE}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|49|23|49|N|13|34|5|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map                     = Czech Republic\n| image_shield                    = \n| image_flag                      = \n| image_skyline                   = Lou\u017en\u00e1, rybn\u00edk.jpg\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Lou\u017en\u00e1''' is a small village, part of and located about 2.5&nbsp;km south of [[Mysl\u00edv]] in the [[Klatovy District|Klatovy district]]. There are 43 addresses registered. \u00a0In 2011, 46 people lived here permanently. It is also a cadastral territory with an area of 3.59&nbsp;km\u00b2.\n\n== History ==\nThe first written mention of the village dates back to 1558<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.obecmysliv.cz/cs/historie-a-pamatky-obce-louzna|title=Historie a pam\u00e1tky obce Lou\u017en\u00e1 {{!}} Obec Mysl\u00edv|website=www.obecmysliv.cz|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> when the village named Lou\u017en\u00e1 is listed in the property of Adam of Sternberg. The village was a part of the Zelenohorsk\u00e9 and then a plan estate, owned by the \u0160ternberks and later Martinice. No information is known about the establishment of the village, but it is likely to be related to the operation of the Cistercian monastery under Zelena Hora.\n\nThe name Lou\u017en\u00e1 means a floodplain village (ie a village lying near a puddle, \"l\u00fa\u017e\u011b\"). Old Czech dictionaries do not accurately reflect the word \"l\u00fa\u017e\u011b\", but it seems that the word also referred to a slightly larger water surface than the word puddle, pool. In the past, the name of the village was recorded in the form: Lauzna, Lauc\u017ena or Lauschna.\n\nThe village has two parts: Stankovy (no. 28 to the north) and Lou\u017en\u00e1 (no. 11 to the south). On the map of the first military survey from the 1860s the village is captured without the later part of Stankovy. At that time, the individual houses were situated practically only around a relatively large village square, on which a large cross was drawn, which preceded the local chapel, and a small pond. Part of Stankovy began to be built in the first half of the 19th century.\n\nAt present, Lou\u017en\u00e1 is an integrated municipality of Mysl\u00edv, including the Mysl\u00edv parish.\n\n=== Chapel of the Virgin Mary Queen ===\nThe chapel on the village square in Lou\u017en\u00e1 was built in 1920. It is dedicated to the Virgin Mary Queen and the pilgrimage is celebrated here on the first Sunday after 24 August. It's rectangular in shape, the roof is covered with tiles. In the 1970s a major repair of the interior of the chapel was made and was plastered from the outside. In 2009 - 2010 the chapel acquired a new roof and a copper bell tower. In front of the chapel stands a monument to the fallen soldiers of the I. and II. World War II, which was in 2011 replaced by a new granite monument and a new plaque.\n\n== Genealogy and Immigration to America ==\nSo far, about 59 people born in Lou\u017en\u00e1 have been identified as immigrating to [[United States|America]], sorted and profiled on [[FamilySearch]]. The earliest was probably Anna Smolikova, who immigrated with her new husband Frantisek Duspiva in 1870 to [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]], finally settling in [[Fayette County, Illinois|Fayette County]], [[Illinois]]. The immigrants are listed as follows (women are paired with their maiden names):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Embarkation\n!Arrival\n!Immigrants\n!Photos\n|-\n|Bark Pallas\nBremen\n|6 July 1870\nBaltimore\n|Smolik - Anna (1844\u20131913) [with her husband Frantisek Duspiva]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:3QSQ-G9Z8-Y62F?cc=2018318&wc=MKZ4-YWY%3A1004777901%2C1004792801|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Smolik|first=|date=1870|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|[[File:Anna Smol\u00edkov\u00e1-Dupsiva (1844-1913).png|center|thumb|Anna Smol\u00edkov\u00e1-Dupsiva (1844-1913)]]\n|-\n|\n|c. 1880\n|Urs - Vaclav (1867\u20131944)\n|\n|-\n|SS Hermann Bremen[[File:SS_Hermann.jpg|alt=|center|thumb|SS Hermann]]\n|7 May 1880\nBaltimore\n|Urs - Josefa (1876\u20131909)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK6L-ZTVQ|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Urs|first=|date=1880|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|SS Rhein\nBremen\n|27 June 1882\nNew York\n|Havlik - Frantisek (1860\u2013), Jan (1863-1937)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:27T7-MSZ|title=New York Passenger Lists, 1820-1891|last=Havlik|first=|date=1882|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|30 October 1884\nSS Hermann Bremen[[File:SS_Hermann.jpg|alt=|center|thumb|SS Hermann]]\n|15 November 1884\nBaltimore\n|Kral - Josef (1847-1896) [with his wife from [[Nehodiv]], Josefa Hulcova, 5 children, Josefa Radova of Stipoklasy, and an unknown Marie Hranickova. He eventually returned to Louzna in 1